# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biosensors-synthetic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers are used in biological lab research and medical tests.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] If multiple aptamers are combined into a single assay, they can measure large numbers of different proteins in a sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] They can be used to identify molecular markers of disease, or can function as drugs, drug delivery systems and controlled drug release systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] They also find use in other molecular engineering tasks.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Most aptamers originate from SELEX, a family of test-tube experiments for finding useful aptamers in a massive pool of different DNA sequences.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This process is much like natural selection, directed evolution or artificial selection.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In SELEX, the researcher repeatedly selects for the best aptamers from a starting DNA library made of about a quadrillion different randomly generated pieces of DNA or RNA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] After SELEX, the researcher might mutate or change the chemistry of the aptamers and do another selection, or might use rational design processes to engineer improvements.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Non-SELEX methods for discovering aptamers also exist.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Researchers optimize aptamers to achieve a variety of beneficial features.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The most important feature is specific and sensitive binding to the chosen target.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] When aptamers are exposed to bodily fluids, as in serum tests or aptamer therapeutics, it is often important for them to resist digestion by DNA- and RNA-destroying enzymes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Therapeutic aptamers often must be modified to clear slowly from the body.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers that change their shape dramatically when they bind their target are useful as molecular switches to turn a sensor on and off.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Some aptamers are engineered to fit into a biosensor or in a test of a biological sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] It can be useful in some cases for the aptamer to accomplish a pre-defined level or speed of binding.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] As the yield of the synthesis used to produce known aptamers shrinks quickly for longer sequences, researchers often truncate aptamers to the minimal binding sequence to reduce the production cost.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The word "aptamer" is a neologism coined by Andrew D.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Ellington and Jack Szostak in their first publication on the topic.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The word itself, however, derives from the Greek word **ἅπτω**, to connect or fit (as used by Homer (c.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] 8th century BC)) and **μέρος,** a component of something larger.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] A typical aptamer is a synthetically generated ligand exploiting the combinatorial diversity of DNA, RNA, XNA, or peptide to achieve strong, specific binding for a particular target molecule or family of target molecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers are occasionally classified as "chemical antibodies" or "antibody mimics".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] However, most aptamers are small, with a molecular weight of 6-30 kDa, in contrast to the 150 kDa size of antibodies, and contain one binding site rather than the two matching antigen binding regions of a typical antibody.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Since its first application in 1967, directed evolution methodologies have been used to develop biomolecules with new properties and functions.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Early examples include the modification of the bacteriophage Qbeta replication system and the generation of ribozymes with modified cleavage activity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Two years later, the Szostak lab and Gilead Sciences, acting independently of one another, used *in vitro* selection schemes to generate DNA aptamers for organic dyes and human thrombin, respectively.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Colin Cox in the Ellington lab, reducing the duration of a weeks-long selection experiment to just three days.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In 2002, two groups led by Ronald Breaker and Evgeny Nudler published the first definitive evidence for a riboswitch, a nucleic acid-based genetic regulatory element, the existence of which had previously been suspected.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Riboswitches possess similar molecular recognition properties to aptamers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This discovery added support to the RNA World hypothesis, a postulated stage in time in the origin of life on Earth.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Most aptamers are based on a specific oligomer sequence of 20-100 bases and 3-20 kDa.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Some have chemical modifications for functional enhancements or compatibility with larger engineered molecular systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] DNA, RNA, XNA, and peptide aptamer chemistries can each offer distinct profiles in terms of shelf stability, durability in serum or *in vivo*, specificity and sensitivity, cost, ease of generation, amplification, and characterization, and familiarity to users.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Typically, DNA- and RNA-based aptamers exhibit low immunogenicity, are amplifiable via Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR), and have complex secondary structure and tertiary structure.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] DNA- and XNA-based aptamers exhibit superior shelf stability.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] XNA-based aptamers can introduce additional chemical diversity to increase binding affinity or greater durability in serum or *in vivo*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] As 22 genetically encoded and over 500 naturally occurring amino acids exist, peptide aptamers, as well as antibodies, have much greater potential combinatorial diversity per unit length relative to the 4 nucleic acids in DNA or RNA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Chemical modifications of nucleic acid bases or backbones increase the chemical diversity of standard nucleic acid bases.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Split aptamers are composed of two or more DNA strands that are pieces of a larger parent aptamer that has been broken in two by a molecular nick.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The ability of each component strand to bind targets will depend on the location of the nick, as well as the secondary structures of the daughter strands.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The presence of a target molecule supports the joining of DNA fragments.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This can be used as the basis for biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Once assembled, the two separate DNA strands can be ligated into a single strand.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Unmodified aptamers are cleared rapidly from the bloodstream, with a half-life of seconds to hours.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This is mainly due to nuclease degradation, which physically destroys the aptamers, as well as clearance by the kidneys, a result of the aptamer's low molecular weight and size.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Several modifications, such as 2'-fluorine-substituted pyrimidines and polyethylene glycol (PEG) linkage, permit a serum half-life of days to weeks.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] PEGylation can add sufficient mass and size to prevent clearance by the kidneys *in vivo*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Unmodified aptamers can treat coagulation disorders.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The problem of clearance and nuclease digestion is diminished when they are applied to the eye, where there is a lower concentration of nuclease and the rate of clearance is lower.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Rapid clearance from serum can also be useful in some applications, such as *in vivo* diagnostic imaging.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In a study on aptamers designed to bind with proteins associated with Ebola infection, a comparison was made among three aptamers isolated for their ability to bind the target protein EBOV sGP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Although these aptamers vary in both sequence and structure, they exhibit remarkably similar relative affinities for sGP from EBOV and SUDV, as well as EBOV GP1.2.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Notably, these aptamers demonstrated a high degree of specificity for the GP gene products.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] One aptamer, in particular, proved effective as a recognition element in an electrochemical sensor, enabling the detection of sGP and GP1.2 in solution, as well as GP1.2 within a membrane context.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The results of this research point to the intriguing possibility that certain regions on protein surfaces may possess aptatropic qualities.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Identifying the key features of such sites, in conjunction with improved 3-D structural predictions for aptamers, holds the potential to enhance the accuracy of predicting aptamer interaction sites on proteins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This, in turn, may help identify aptamers with a heightened likelihood of binding proteins with high affinity, as well as shed light on protein mutations that could significantly impact aptamer binding.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This comprehensive understanding of the structure-based interactions between aptamers and proteins is vital for refining the computational predictability of aptamer-protein binding.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Moreover, it has the potential to eventually eliminate the need for the experimental SELEX protocol.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamer targets can include small molecules and heavy metal ions, larger ligands such as proteins, and even whole cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] These targets include lysozyme, thrombin, human immunodeficiency virus trans-acting responsive element (HIV TAR), hemin, interferon γ, vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), prostate specific antigen (PSA), dopamine, and the non-classical oncogene, heat shock factor 1 (HSF1).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers have been generated against cancer cells, prions, bacteria, and viruses.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Viral targets of aptamers include influenza A and B viruses, Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), SARS coronavirus (SARS-CoV) and SARS-CoV-2.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers may be particularly useful for environmental science proteomics.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Antibodies, like other proteins, are more difficult to sequence than nucleic acids.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] They are also costly to maintain and produce, and are at constant risk of contamination, as they are produced via cell culture or are harvested from animal serum.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] For this reason, researchers interested in little-studied proteins and species may find that companies will not produce, maintain, or adequately validate the quality of antibodies against their target of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] By contrast, aptamers are simple to sequence and cost nothing to maintain, as their exact structure can be stored digitally and synthesized on demand.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This may make them more economically feasible as research tools for underfunded biological research subjects.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers exist for plant compounds, such as theophylline (found in tea) and abscisic acid (a plant immune hormone).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] An aptamer against a-amanitin (the toxin that causes lethal *Amanita* poisoning) has been developed, an example of an aptamer against a mushroom target.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamer applications can be roughly grouped into sensing, therapeutic, reagent production, and engineering categories.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Sensing applications are important in environmental, biomedical, epidemiological, biosecurity, and basic research applications, where aptamers act as probes in assays, imaging methods, diagnostic assays, and biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In therapeutic applications and precision medicine, aptamers can function as drugs, as targeted drug delivery vehicles, as controlled release mechanisms, and as reagents for drug discovery via high-throughput screening for small molecules and proteins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers have application for protein production monitoring, quality control, and purification.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] They can function in molecular engineering applications as a way to modify proteins, such as enhancing DNA polymerase to make PCR more reliable.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Because the affinity of the aptamer also affects its dynamic range and limit of detection, aptamers with a lower affinity may be desirable when assaying high concentrations of a target molecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Affinity chromatography also depends on the ability of the affinity reagent, such as an aptamer, to bind and release its target, and lower affinities may aid in the release of the target molecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Hence, specific applications determine the useful range for aptamer affinity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers can replace antibodies in many biotechnology applications.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In laboratory research and clinical diagnostics, they can be used in aptamer-based versions of immunoassays including enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), western blot, immunohistochemistry (IHC), and flow cytometry.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] As therapeutics, they can function as agonists or antagonists of their ligand.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] While antibodies are a familiar technology with a well-developed market, aptamers are a relatively new technology to most researchers, and aptamers have been generated against only a fraction of important research targets.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Unlike antibodies, unmodified aptamers are more susceptible to nuclease digestion in serum and renal clearance *in vivo*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamers are much smaller in size and mass than antibodies, which could be a relevant factor in choosing which is best suited for a given application.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In addition, aptamers contribute to reduction of research animal use.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] While antibodies often rely on animals for initial discovery, as well as for production in the case of polyclonal antibodies, both the selection and production of aptamers is typically animal-free.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] However, phage display methods allow for selection of antibodies in vitro, followed by production from a monoclonal cell line, avoiding the use of animals entirely.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The ability of aptamers to reversibly bind molecules such as proteins has generated increasing interest in using them to facilitate controlled release of therapeutic biomolecules, such as growth factors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This can be accomplished by tuning the binding strength to passively release the growth factors, along with active release via mechanisms such as hybridization of the aptamer with complementary oligonucleotides or unfolding of the aptamer due to cellular traction forces.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Aptamer, known for their ability to bind specific molecules reversibly, have been used in 3D bioprinting tissues to precisely deliver growth factors to promote vascularization.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This controlled delivery allows growth factors to be released at the right place and time, encouraging the formation of localized and complex vascular networks.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Additionally, the properties of these networks can be fine-tuned by adjusting how growth factors are released over time, making this approach a powerful tool for creating vascularized engineered tissues.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] AptaBiD (Aptamer-Facilitated Biomarker Discovery) is an aptamer-based method for biomarker discovery.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] While most aptamers are based on DNA, RNA, or XNA, peptide aptamers are artificial proteins selected or engineered to bind specific target molecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Peptide aptamers consist of one or more peptide loops of variable sequence displayed by a protein scaffold.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Derivatives known as tadpoles, in which peptide aptamer "heads" are covalently linked to unique sequence double-stranded DNA "tails", allow quantification of scarce target molecules in mixtures by PCR (using, for example, the quantitative real-time polymerase chain reaction) of their DNA tails.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The peptides that form the aptamer variable regions are synthesized as part of the same polypeptide chain as the scaffold and are constrained at their N and C termini by linkage to it.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] This double structural constraint decreases the diversity of the 3D structures that the variable regions can adopt, and this reduction in structural diversity lowers the entropic cost of molecular binding when interaction with the target causes the variable regions to adopt a uniform structure.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The most common peptide aptamer selection system is the yeast two-hybrid system.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Peptide aptamers can also be selected from combinatorial peptide libraries constructed by phage display and other surface display technologies such as mRNA display, ribosome display, bacterial display and yeast display.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] These experimental procedures are also known as biopanning.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] All the peptides panned from combinatorial peptide libraries have been stored in the MimoDB database.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Libraries of peptide aptamers have been used as "mutagens", in studies in which an investigator introduces a library that expresses different peptide aptamers into a cell population, selects for a desired phenotype, and identifies those aptamers that cause the phenotype.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The investigator then uses those aptamers as baits, for example in yeast two-hybrid screens to identify the cellular proteins targeted by those aptamers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Such experiments identify particular proteins bound by the aptamers, and protein interactions that the aptamers disrupt, to cause the phenotype.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] In addition, peptide aptamers derivatized with appropriate functional moieties can cause specific post-translational modification of their target proteins, or change the subcellular localization of the targets.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Commercial products and companies based on aptamers include the drug Macugen (pegaptanib) and the clinical diagnostic company SomaLogic.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] The International Society on Aptamers (INSOAP), a professional society for the aptamer research community, publishes a journal devoted to the topic, *Aptamers*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/aptamer] Apta-index is a current database cataloging and simplifying the ordering process for over 700 aptamers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In most cases, the principal chemical reaction in bioluminescence involves the reaction of a substrate called luciferin and an enzyme, called luciferase.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Because these are generic names, luciferins and luciferases are often distinguished by the species or group, e.g. firefly luciferin or cypridina luciferin.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In all characterized cases, the enzyme catalyzes the oxidation of the luciferin resulting in excited state oxyluciferin, which is the light emitter of the reaction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Upon their decay to the ground state they emit visible light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In some species, the luciferase requires other cofactors, such as calcium or magnesium ions, and sometimes also the energy-carrying molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In evolution, luciferins vary little: one in particular, coelenterazine, is found in 11 different animal phyla, though in some of these, the animals obtain it through their diet.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Conversely, luciferases vary widely between different species.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence has arisen over 40 times in evolutionary history.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Both Aristotle and Pliny the Elder mention that damp wood sometimes gives off a glow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Many centuries later Robert Boyle showed that oxygen was involved in the process, in wood, fish, and glowworms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It was not until the late nineteenth century that bioluminescence was properly investigated.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The phenomenon is widely distributed among animal groups, especially in marine environments.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] On land it occurs in fungi, bacteria and some groups of invertebrates, including insects.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The uses of bioluminescence by animals include counterillumination camouflage, mimicry of other animals, for example to lure prey, and signaling to other individuals of the same species, such as to attract mates.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In the laboratory, luciferase-based systems are used in genetic engineering and biomedical research.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Before the development of the safety lamp for use in coal mines, dried fish skins were used in Britain and Europe as a weak source of light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This experimental form of illumination avoided the necessity of using candles which risked sparking explosions of firedamp.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Newton Harvey published a monograph, *The Nature of Animal Light*, summarizing early work on bioluminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Harvey notes that Aristotle mentions light produced by dead fish and flesh, and that both Aristotle and Pliny the Elder (in his *Natural History*) mention light from damp wood.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He records that Robert Boyle experimented on these light sources, and showed that both they and the glowworm require air for light to be produced.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Baker identified the flagellate *Noctiluca* "as a luminous animal" "just visible to the naked eye", and in 1854 Johann Florian Heller (1813–1871) identified strands (hyphae) of fungi as the source of light in dead wood.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] James Hingston Tuckey, in his posthumous 1818 *Narrative of the Expedition to the Zaire*, described catching the animals responsible for luminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He mentions pellucida, crustaceans (to which he ascribes the milky whiteness of the water), and cancers (shrimps and crabs).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Under the microscope he described the "luminous property" to be in the brain, resembling "a most brilliant amethyst about the size of a large pin's head".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Darwin also observed a luminous "jelly-fish of the genus Dianaea", noting that: "When the waves scintillate with bright green sparks, I believe it is generally owing to minute crustacea.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] But there can be no doubt that very many other pelagic animals, when alive, are phosphorescent." He guessed that "a disturbed electrical condition of the atmosphere" was probably responsible.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Daniel Pauly comments that Darwin "was lucky with most of his guesses, but not here", noting that biochemistry was too little known, and that the complex evolution of the marine animals involved "would have been too much for comfort".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence attracted the attention of the United States Navy in the Cold War, since submarines in some waters can create a bright enough wake to be detected; a German submarine was sunk in the First World War, having been detected in this way.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The Navy was interested in predicting when such detection would be possible, and hence guiding their own submarines to avoid detection.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Among the anecdotes of navigation by bioluminescence is one recounted by the Apollo 13 astronaut Jim Lovell, who as a Navy pilot had found his way back to his aircraft carrier USS *Shangri-La* when his navigation systems failed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Turning off his cabin lights, he saw the glowing wake of the ship, and was able to fly to it and land safely.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The French pharmacologist Raphaël Dubois carried out work on bioluminescence in the late nineteenth century.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He studied click beetles (*Pyrophorus*) and the marine bivalve mollusc *Pholas dactylus*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He refuted the old idea that bioluminescence came from phosphorus, and demonstrated that the process was related to the oxidation of a specific compound, which he named luciferin, by an enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He sent Harvey siphons from the mollusc preserved in sugar.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Harvey had become interested in bioluminescence as a result of visiting the South Pacific and Japan and observing phosphorescent organisms there.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He studied the phenomenon for many years.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] His research aimed to demonstrate that luciferin, and the enzymes that act on it to produce light, were interchangeable between species, showing that all bioluminescent organisms had a common ancestor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, he found this hypothesis to be false, with different organisms having major differences in the composition of their light-producing proteins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He spent the next 30 years purifying and studying the components, but it fell to the young Japanese chemist Osamu Shimomura to be the first to obtain crystalline luciferin.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] He used the sea firefly *Vargula hilgendorfii*, but it was another ten years before he discovered the chemical's structure and published his 1957 paper *Crystalline Cypridina Luciferin*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Tsien won the 2008 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their 1961 discovery and development of green fluorescent protein as a tool for biological research.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Harvey wrote a detailed historical account on all forms of luminescence in 1957.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] An updated book on bioluminescence covering also the twentieth and early twenty-first century was published recently.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Harvey was among the first to propose how bioluminescence could have evolved.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In this early paper, he suggested that proto-bioluminescence could have arisen from respiratory chain proteins that hold fluorescent groups.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This hypothesis has since been disproven, but it did lead to considerable interest in the origins of the phenomenon.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Today, the two prevailing hypotheses (both concerning marine bioluminescence) are those put forth by Howard Seliger in 1993 and Rees et al. in 1998.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Seliger's theory identifies luciferase enzymes as the catalyst for the evolution of bioluminescent systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It suggests that the original purpose of luciferases was as mixed-function oxygenases.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] As the early ancestors of many species moved into deeper and darker waters natural selection favored the development of increased eye sensitivity and enhanced visual signals.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] If selection were to favor a mutation in the oxygenase enzyme required for the breakdown of pigment molecules (molecules often associated with spots used to attract a mate or distract a predator) it could have eventually resulted in external luminescence in tissues.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Rees et al. use evidence gathered from the marine luciferin coelenterazine to suggest that selection acting on luciferins may have arisen from pressures to protect oceanic organisms from potentially deleterious reactive oxygen species (e.g.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The functional shift from antioxidation to bioluminescence probably occurred when the strength of selection for antioxidation defense decreased as early species moved further down the water column.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] At greater depths exposure to ROS is significantly lower, as is the endogenous production of ROS through metabolism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] While popular at first, Seliger's theory has been challenged, particularly on the biochemical and genetic evidence that Rees examines.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] What remains clear, however, is that bioluminescence has evolved independently at least 40 times.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence in fish began at least by the Cretaceous period.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] About 1,500 fish species are known to be bioluminescent; the capability evolved independently at least 27 times.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Of these, 17 involved the taking up of bioluminous bacteria from the surrounding water while in the others, the intrinsic light evolved through chemical synthesis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These fish have become surprisingly diverse in the deep ocean and control their light with the help of their nervous system, using it not just to lure prey or hide from predators, but also for communication.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] All bioluminescent organisms have in common that the reaction of a "luciferin" and oxygen is catalyzed by a luciferase to produce light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] McElroy and Seliger proposed in 1962 that the bioluminescent reaction evolved to detoxify oxygen, in parallel with photosynthesis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence has evolved independently at least 94 times, first emerging in octocorals some 540 million years ago.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It has evolved independently 27 times within the ray-finned fishes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The oldest of these appear to be Stomiiformes and Myctophidae.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Genomic analysis of octocorals indicates that their ancestor was bioluminescent as long as 540 million years ago.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence is a form of chemiluminescence where light energy is released by a chemical reaction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This reaction involves a light-emitting pigment, the luciferin, and a luciferase, the enzyme component.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Because of the diversity of luciferin/luciferase combinations, there are very few commonalities in the chemical mechanism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] From currently studied systems, a unifying mechanism is the role of molecular oxygen; often there is a concurrent release of carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] For example, the firefly luciferin/luciferase reaction requires magnesium and ATP and produces CO2, adenosine monophosphate (AMP) and pyrophosphate (PP) as waste products.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Other cofactors may be required, such as calcium (Ca2+) for the photoprotein aequorin, or magnesium (Mg2+) ions and ATP for the firefly luciferase.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The production of the excited state molecules always involves the decomposition of organic peroxides.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Instead of a luciferase, the jellyfish *Aequorea victoria* makes use of another type of protein called a photoprotein, in this case specifically aequorin.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] When calcium ions are added, rapid catalysis creates a brief flash quite unlike the prolonged glow produced by luciferase.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In a second, much slower step, luciferin is regenerated from the oxidized (oxyluciferin) form, allowing it to recombine with aequorin, in preparation for a subsequent flash.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Photoproteins are thus enzymes, but with unusual reaction kinetics.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Furthermore, some of the blue light released by aequorin in contact with calcium ions is absorbed by a green fluorescent protein, which in turn releases green light in a process called resonant energy transfer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Not all these organisms synthesise coelenterazine: some of them obtain it through their diet.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Conversely, luciferase enzymes vary widely and tend to be different in each species.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence occurs widely among animals, especially in the open sea, including fish, jellyfish, comb jellies, crustaceans, and cephalopod molluscs; in some fungi and bacteria; and in various terrestrial invertebrates, nearly all of which are beetles.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In marine coastal habitats, about 2.5% of organisms are estimated to be bioluminescent, whereas in pelagic habitats in the eastern Pacific, about 76% of the main taxa of deep-sea animals have been found to be capable of producing light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] More than 700 animal genera have been recorded with light-producing species.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Most marine light-emission is in the blue and green light spectrum.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, some loose-jawed fish emit red and infrared light, and the genus *Tomopteris* emits yellow light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The most frequently encountered bioluminescent organisms may be the dinoflagellates in the surface layers of the sea, which are responsible for the sparkling luminescence sometimes seen at night in disturbed water.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] At least 18 genera of these phytoplankton exhibit luminosity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Luminescent dinoflagellate ecosystems are present in warm water lagoons and bays with narrow openings to the ocean.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] A different effect is the thousands of square miles of the ocean which shine with the light produced by bioluminescent bacteria, known as mareel or the milky seas effect.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence is abundant in the pelagic zone, with the most concentration at depths devoid of light and surface waters at night.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These organisms participate in diurnal vertical migration from the dark depths to the surface at night, dispersing the population of bioluminescent organisms across the pelagic water column.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The dispersal of bioluminescence across different depths in the pelagic zone has been attributed to the selection pressures imposed by predation and the lack of places to hide in the open sea.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In depths where sunlight never penetrates, often below 200m, the significance of bioluminescent is evident in the retainment of functional eyes for organisms to detect bioluminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Organisms often produce bioluminescence themselves, rarely do they generate it from outside phenomena.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, there are occasions where bioluminescence is produced by bacterial symbionts that have a symbiotic relationship with the host organism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Although many luminous bacteria in the marine environment are free-living, a majority are found in symbiotic relationships that involve fish, squids, crustaceans etc. as hosts.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Most luminous bacteria inhabit the sea, dominated by *Photobacterium* and *Vibrio*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In the symbiotic relationship, bacterium benefit from having a source of nourishment and a refuge to grow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Hosts obtain these bacterial symbionts either from the environment, spawning, or the luminous bacterium is evolving with their host.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Coevolutionary interactions are suggested as host organisms' anatomical adaptations have become specific to only certain luminous bacteria, to suffice ecological dependence of bioluminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence is widely studied amongst species located in the mesopelagic zone, but the benthic zone at mesopelagic depths has remained widely unknown.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Benthic habitats at depths beyond the mesopelagic are also poorly understood due to the same constraints.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Unlike the pelagic zone where the emission of light is undisturbed in the open sea, the occurrence of bioluminescence in the benthic zone is less common.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It has been attributed to the blockage of emitted light by a number of sources such as the sea floor, and inorganic and organic structures.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Visual signals and communication that is prevalent in the pelagic zone such as counter-illumination may not be functional or relevant in the benthic realm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence in bathyal benthic species still remains poorly studied due to difficulties of the collection of species at these depths.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence has several functions in different taxa.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It is much easier for researchers to detect that a species is able to produce light than to analyze the chemical mechanisms or to prove what function the light serves.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In some cases the function is unknown, as with species in three families of earthworm (Oligochaeta), such as *Diplocardia longa,* where the coelomic fluid produces light when the animal moves.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The following functions are reasonably well established in the named organisms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In many animals of the deep sea, including several squid species, bacterial bioluminescence is used for camouflage by counterillumination, in which the animal matches the overhead environmental light as seen from below.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In these animals, photoreceptors control the illumination to match the brightness of the background.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These light organs are usually separate from the tissue containing the bioluminescent bacteria.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, in one species, *Euprymna scolopes*, the bacteria are an integral component of the animal's light organ.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence is used in a variety of ways and for different purposes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The cirrate octopod *Stauroteuthis syrtensis* uses emits bioluminescence from its sucker like structures.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These structures are believed to have evolved from what are more commonly known as octopus suckers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] They do not have the same function as the normal suckers because they no longer have any handling or grappling ability due its evolution of photophores.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The placement of the photophores are within the animals oral reach, which leads researchers to suggest that it uses it bioluminescence to capture and lure prey.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Two systems are involved according to species; in one, females emit light from their abdomens to attract males; in the other, flying males emit signals to which the sometimes sedentary females respond.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Click beetles emit an orange light from the abdomen when flying and a green light from the thorax when they are disturbed or moving about on the ground.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The former is probably a sexual attractant but the latter may be defensive.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Larvae of the click beetle *Pyrophorus nyctophanus* live in the surface layers of termite mounds in Brazil.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] They light up the mounds by emitting a bright greenish glow which attracts the flying insects on which they feed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In the marine environment, use of luminescence for mate attraction is chiefly known among ostracods, small shrimp-like crustaceans, especially in the family Cyprididae.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Pheromones may be used for long-distance communication, with bioluminescence used at close range to enable mates to "home in".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] A polychaete worm, the Bermuda fireworm creates a brief display, a few nights after the full moon, when the female lights up to attract males.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The defense mechanisms for bioluminescent organisms can come in multiple forms; startling prey, counter-illumination, smoke screen or misdirection, distractive body parts, burglar alarm, sacrificial tag or warning coloration.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The shrimp family Oplophoridae Dana use their bioluminescence as a way of startling the predator that is after them.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] *Acanthephyra purpurea*, within the Oplophoridae family, uses its photophores to emit light, and can secrete a bioluminescent substance when in the presence of a predator.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This secretory mechanism is common among prey fish.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Many cephalopods, including at least 70 genera of squid, are bioluminescent.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Some squid and small crustaceans use bioluminescent chemical mixtures or bacterial slurries in the same way as many squid use ink.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] A cloud of luminescent material is expelled, distracting or repelling a potential predator, while the animal escapes to safety.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The deep sea squid *Octopoteuthis deletron* may autotomize portions of its arms which are luminous and continue to twitch and flash, thus distracting a predator while the animal flees.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Dinoflagellates may use bioluminescence for defense against predators.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, the specific explanation as to why predators are deterred by bioluminescence is still debated.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Dinoflagellates shine when they detect a predator, possibly making the predator itself more vulnerable by attracting the attention of predators from higher trophic levels (better known as the "burglar alarm hypothesis").
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The problem of shining stomach contents is solved (and the explanation corroborated) in predatory deep-sea fishes: their stomachs have a black lining able to keep the light from any bioluminescent fish prey which they have swallowed from attracting larger predators.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The sea-firefly is a small crustacean living in sediment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] At rest it emits a dull glow but when disturbed it darts away leaving a cloud of shimmering blue light to confuse the predator.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] During World War II it was gathered and dried for use by the Japanese army as a source of light during clandestine operations.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The larvae of railroad worms (*Phrixothrix*) have paired photic organs on each body segment, able to glow with green light; these are thought to have a defensive purpose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] They also have organs on the head which produce red light; they are the only terrestrial organisms to emit light of this color.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Aposematism is a widely used function of bioluminescence, providing a warning that the creature concerned is unpalatable.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It is suggested that many firefly larvae glow to repel predators; some millipedes glow for the same purpose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Some marine organisms are believed to emit light for a similar reason.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These include scale worms, jellyfish and brittle stars but further research is needed to fully establish the function of the luminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Such a mechanism would be of particular advantage to soft-bodied cnidarians if they were able to deter predation in this way.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The limpet *Latia neritoides* is the only known freshwater gastropod that emits light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It produces greenish luminescent mucus which may have an anti-predator function.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The marine snail *Hinea brasiliana* uses flashes of light, probably to deter predators.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The blue-green light is emitted through the translucent shell, which functions as an efficient diffuser of light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Communication in the form of quorum sensing plays a role in the regulation of luminescence in many species of bacteria.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Small extracellularly secreted molecules stimulate the bacteria to turn on genes for light production when cell density, measured by concentration of the secreted molecules, is high.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Pyrosomes are colonial tunicates and each zooid has a pair of luminescent organs on either side of the inlet siphon.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] When stimulated by light, these turn on and off, causing rhythmic flashing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] No neural pathway runs between the zooids, but each responds to the light produced by other individuals, and even to light from other nearby colonies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Communication by light emission between the zooids enables coordination of colony effort, for example in swimming where each zooid provides part of the propulsive force.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Some bioluminous bacteria infect nematodes that parasitize Lepidoptera larvae.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] When these caterpillars die, their luminosity may attract predators to the dead insect thus assisting in the dispersal of both bacteria and nematodes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] A similar reason may account for the many species of fungi that emit light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Species in the genera *Armillaria*, *Mycena*, *Omphalotus*, *Panellus*, *Pleurotus* and others do this, emitting usually greenish light from the mycelium, cap and gills.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This may attract night-flying insects and aid in spore dispersal, but other functions may also be involved.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescence is used by a variety of animals to mimic other species.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Many species of deep sea fish such as the anglerfish and dragonfish make use of aggressive mimicry to attract prey.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] They have an appendage on their heads called an esca that contains bioluminescent bacteria able to produce a long-lasting glow which the fish can control.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The glowing esca is dangled or waved about to lure small animals to within striking distance of the fish.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The cookiecutter shark uses bioluminescence to camouflage its underside by counter-illumination, but a small patch near its pectoral fins remains dark, appearing as a small fish to large predatory fish like tuna and mackerel swimming beneath it.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] When such fish approach the lure, they are bitten by the shark.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Female *Photuris* fireflies sometimes mimic the light pattern of another firefly, *Photinus*, to attract its males as prey.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In this way they obtain both food and the defensive chemicals named lucibufagins, which *Photuris* cannot synthesize.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] South American giant cockroaches of the genus *Lucihormetica* were believed to be the first known example of defensive mimicry, emitting light in imitation of bioluminescent, poisonous click beetles.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] However, doubt has been cast on this assertion, and there is no conclusive evidence that the cockroaches are bioluminescent.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] While most marine bioluminescence is green to blue, some deep sea barbeled dragonfishes in the genera *Aristostomias*, *Pachystomias* and *Malacosteus* emit a red glow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] This adaptation allows the fish to see red-pigmented prey, which are normally invisible to other organisms in the deep ocean environment where red light has been filtered out by the water column.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] These fish are able to utilize the longer wavelength to act as a spotlight for its prey that only they can see.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The fish may also use this light to communicate with each other to find potential mates.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The ability of the fish to see this light is explained by the presence of specialized rhodopsin pigment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The mechanism of light creation is through a suborbital photophore that utilizes gland cells which produce exergonic chemical reactions that produce light with a longer, red wavelength.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The dragonfish species which produce the red light also produce blue light in photophore on the dorsal area.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The main function of this is to alert the fish to the presence of its prey.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The additional pigment is thought to be assimilated from chlorophyll derivatives found in the copepods which form part of its diet.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The angler siphonophore (*Erenna*) utilizes red bioluminescence in appendages to lure fish.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescent organisms are a target for many areas of research.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Luciferase systems are widely used in genetic engineering as reporter genes, and for biomedical research using bioluminescence imaging.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] For example, the firefly luciferase gene was used as early as 1986 for research using transgenic tobacco plants.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] *Vibrio* bacteria symbiose with marine invertebrates such as the Hawaiian bobtail squid (*Euprymna scolopes*), are key experimental models for bioluminescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Bioluminescent activated destruction is an experimental cancer treatment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The structures of photophores, the light producing organs in bioluminescent organisms, are being investigated by industrial designers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Engineered bioluminescence could perhaps one day be used to reduce the need for street lighting, or for decorative purposes if it becomes possible to produce light that is both bright enough and can be sustained for long periods at a workable price.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The gene that makes the tails of fireflies glow has been added to mustard plants.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] The plants glow faintly for an hour when touched, but a sensitive camera is needed to see the glow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] University of Wisconsin–Madison is researching the use of genetically engineered bioluminescent E. coli bacteria, for use as bioluminescent bacteria in a light bulb.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In 2011, Philips demonstrated a microbial system for ambience lighting in the home.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] An iGEM team from Cambridge (England) has started to address the problem that luciferin is consumed in the light-producing reaction by developing a genetic biotechnology part that codes for a luciferin regenerating enzyme from the North American firefly.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In 2016, Glowee, a French company started selling bioluminescent lights for shop fronts and street signs, for use between 1 and 7 in the morning when the law forbids use of electricity for this purpose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] They used the bioluminescent bacterium *Aliivibrio fischeri*, but the maximum lifetime of their product was three days.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] In April 2020, plants were genetically engineered to glow more brightly using genes from the bioluminescent mushroom *Neonothopanus nambi* to convert caffeic acid into luciferin.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Another possible application is to replace chemiluminescence with bioluminescent enzymes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] A Canadian company, Lux Bio, is developing long-duration bioluminescent enzymes for this purpose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] ATP bioluminescence is the process in which ATP is used to generate luminescence in an organism, in conjunction with other compounds such as luciferin.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] It proves to be a very good biosensor to test for the presence of living microbes in water.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] Different types of microbial populations are determined through different sets of ATP assays using other substrates and reagents.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/bioluminescence] *Renilla*- and *Gaussia*-based cell viability assays use the substrate coelenterazine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A **biosensor** (or **nanobiosensor** in the nanoscale) is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The *sensitive biological element*, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This sometimes accounts for the most expensive part of the sensor device, however it is possible to generate a user friendly display that includes transducer and sensitive element (holographic sensor).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The readers are usually custom-designed and manufactured to suit the different working principles of biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A biosensor typically consists of a bio-receptor (enzyme/antibody/cell/nucleic acid/aptamer), transducer component (semi-conducting material/nanomaterial), and electronic system which includes a signal amplifier, processor & display.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Transducers and electronics can be combined, e.g., in CMOS-based microsensor systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The recognition component, often called a bioreceptor, uses biomolecules from organisms or receptors modeled after biological systems to interact with the analyte of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This interaction is measured by the biotransducer which outputs a measurable signal proportional to the presence of the target analyte in the sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The general aim of the design of a biosensor is to enable quick, convenient testing at the point of concern or care where the sample was procured.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In a biosensor, the bioreceptor is designed to interact with the specific analyte of interest to produce an effect measurable by the transducer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] High selectivity for the analyte among a matrix of other chemical or biological components is a key requirement of the bioreceptor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] While the type of biomolecule used can vary widely, biosensors can be classified according to common types of bioreceptor interactions involving: antibody/antigen, enzymes/ligands, nucleic acids/DNA, cellular structures/cells, or biomimetic materials.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An immunosensor utilizes the very specific binding affinity of antibodies for a specific compound or antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The specific nature of the antibody-antigen interaction is analogous to a lock and key fit in that the antigen will only bind to the antibody if it has the correct conformation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Binding events result in a physicochemical change that in combination with a tracer, such as fluorescent molecules, enzymes, or radioisotopes, can generate a signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There are limitations with using antibodies in sensors: 1.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The antibody binding capacity is strongly dependent on assay conditions (e.g. pH and temperature), and 2. the antibody-antigen interaction is generally robust, however, binding can be disrupted by chaotropic reagents, organic solvents, or even ultrasonic radiation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Antibody-antigen interactions can also be used for serological testing, or the detection of circulating antibodies in response to a specific disease.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Importantly, serology tests have become an important part of the global response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The use of antibodies as the bio-recognition component of biosensors has several drawbacks.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] They have high molecular weights and limited stability, contain essential disulfide bonds and are expensive to produce.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In one approach to overcome these limitations, recombinant binding fragments (Fab, Fv or scFv) or domains (VH, VHH) of antibodies have been engineered.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In another approach, small protein scaffolds with favorable biophysical properties have been engineered to generate artificial families of Antigen Binding Proteins (AgBP), capable of specific binding to different target proteins while retaining the favorable properties of the parent molecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The elements of the family that specifically bind to a given target antigen, are often selected in vitro by display techniques: phage display, ribosome display, yeast display or mRNA display.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The artificial binding proteins are much smaller than antibodies (usually less than 100 amino-acid residues), have a strong stability, lack disulfide bonds and can be expressed in high yield in reducing cellular environments like the bacterial cytoplasm, contrary to antibodies and their derivatives.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] They are thus especially suitable to create biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The specific binding capabilities and catalytic activity of enzymes make them popular bioreceptors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Notably, since enzymes are not consumed in reactions, the biosensor can easily be used continuously.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The catalytic activity of enzymes also allows lower limits of detection compared to common binding techniques.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] However, the sensor's lifetime is limited by the stability of the enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Antibodies have a high binding constant in excess of 10^8 L/mol, which stands for a nearly irreversible association once the antigen-antibody couple has formed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] For certain analyte molecules like glucose affinity binding proteins exist that bind their ligand with a high specificity like an antibody, but with a much smaller binding constant on the order of 10^2 to 10^4 L/mol.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The association between analyte and receptor then is of reversible nature and next to the couple between both also their free molecules occur in a measurable concentration.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In case of glucose, for instance, concanavalin A may function as affinity receptor exhibiting a binding constant of 4x10^2 L/mol.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The use of affinity binding receptors for purposes of biosensing has been proposed by Schultz and Sims in 1979 and was subsequently configured into a fluorescent assay for measuring glucose in the relevant physiological range between 4.4 and 6.1 mmol/L.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The sensor principle has the advantage that it does not consume the analyte in a chemical reaction as occurs in enzymatic assays.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensors employing nucleic acid based receptors can be either based on complementary base pairing interactions referred to as genosensors or specific nucleic acid based antibody mimics (aptamers) as aptasensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In the former, the recognition process is based on the principle of complementary base pairing, adenine:thymine and cytosine:guanine in DNA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] If the target nucleic acid sequence is known, complementary sequences can be synthesized, labeled, and then immobilized on the sensor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The hybridization event can be optically detected and presence of target DNA/RNA ascertained.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In the latter, aptamers generated against the target recognise it via interplay of specific non-covalent interactions and induced fitting.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] These aptamers can be labelled with a fluorophore/metal nanoparticles easily for optical detection or may be employed for label-free electrochemical or cantilever based detection platforms for a wide range of target molecules or complex targets like cells and viruses.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Additionally, aptamers can be combined with nucleic acid enzymes, such as RNA-cleaving DNAzymes, providing both target recognition and signal generation in a single molecule, which shows potential applications in the development of multiplex biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] It has been proposed that properly optimized integrated optical resonators can be exploited for detecting epigenetic modifications (e.g.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] DNA methylation, histone post-translational modifications) in body fluids from patients affected by cancer or other diseases.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Photonic biosensors with ultra-sensitivity are nowadays being developed at a research level to easily detect cancerous cells within the patient's urine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Different research projects aim to develop new portable devices that use cheap, environmentally friendly, disposable cartridges that require only simple handling with no need of further processing, washing, or manipulation by expert technicians.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Organelles form separate compartments inside cells and usually perform functions independently.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Different kinds of organelles have various metabolic pathways and contain enzymes to fulfill its function.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Commonly used organelles include lysosome, chloroplast and mitochondria.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The spatial-temporal distribution pattern of calcium is closely related to ubiquitous signaling pathway.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Mitochondria actively participate in the metabolism of calcium ions to control the function and also modulate the calcium related signaling pathways.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Experiments have proved that mitochondria have the ability to respond to high calcium concentrations generated in their proximity by opening the calcium channels.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In this way, mitochondria can be used to detect the calcium concentration in medium and the detection is very sensitive due to high spatial resolution.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Another application of mitochondria is used for detection of water pollution.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Detergent compounds' toxicity will damage the cell and subcellular structure including mitochondria.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The detergents will cause a swelling effect which could be measured by an absorbance change.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Experiment data shows the change rate is proportional to the detergent concentration, providing a high standard for detection accuracy.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Cells are often used in bioreceptors because they are sensitive to surrounding environment and they can respond to all kinds of stimulants.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Cells tend to attach to the surface so they can be easily immobilized.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Compared to organelles they remain active for longer period and the reproducibility makes them reusable.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] They are commonly used to detect global parameter like stress condition, toxicity and organic derivatives.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] They can also be used to monitor the treatment effect of drugs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] One application is to use cells to determine herbicides which are main aquatic contaminant.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Microalgae are entrapped on a quartz microfiber and the chlorophyll fluorescence modified by herbicides is collected at the tip of an optical fiber bundle and transmitted to a fluorimeter.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The algae are continuously cultured to get optimized measurement.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Results show that detection limit of certain herbicide can reach sub-ppb concentration level.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Some cells can also be used to monitor the microbial corrosion.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Pseudomonas sp. is isolated from corroded material surface and immobilized on acetylcellulose membrane.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The respiration activity is determined by measuring oxygen consumption.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There is linear relationship between the current generated and the concentration of sulfuric acid.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The response time is related to the loading of cells and surrounding environments and can be controlled to no more than 5min.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Tissues are used for biosensor for the abundance of enzymes existing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There also exist some disadvantages of tissues, like the lack of specificity due to the interference of other enzymes and longer response time due to the transport barrier.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Microbial biosensors exploit the response of bacteria to a given substance.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] For example, arsenic can be detected using the ars operon found in several bacterial taxon.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An important part of a biosensor is to attach the biological elements (small molecules/protein/cells) to the surface of the sensor (be it metal, polymer, or glass).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The simplest way is to functionalize the surface in order to coat it with the biological elements.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This can be done by polylysine, aminosilane, epoxysilane, or nitrocellulose in the case of silicon chips/silica glass.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Subsequently, the bound biological agent may also be fixed—for example, by layer by layer deposition of alternatively charged polymer coatings.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The most commonly used hydrogel is sol-gel, glassy silica generated by polymerization of silicate monomers (added as tetra alkyl orthosilicates, such as TMOS or TEOS) in the presence of the biological elements (along with other stabilizing polymers, such as PEG) in the case of physical entrapment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Another group of hydrogels, which set under conditions suitable for cells or protein, are acrylate hydrogel, which polymerizes upon radical initiation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Smart materials that mimic the biological components of a sensor can also be classified as biosensors using only the active or catalytic site or analogous configurations of a biomolecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensors can be classified by their biotransducer type.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Electrochemical biosensors combine the exquisite selectivity of biological recognition elements with the high sensitivity and rapid response times of electrochemical transduction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] To understand their design and application, these systems can be systematically categorized by their electrical measurement techniques and their biorecognition mechanisms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Electrochemical biosensors are broadly divided into **active techniques** (which force a current or voltage change upon the system to measure a dynamic response) and **passive techniques** (which measure a system at equilibrium or under resting conditions).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Regardless of the electrical technique used to read out the signal, the specificity of the biosensor depends entirely on its biological layer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The use of ion channels has been shown to offer highly sensitive detection of target biological molecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] By embedding the ion channels in supported or tethered bilayer membranes (t-BLM) attached to a gold electrode, an electrical circuit is created.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Capture molecules such as antibodies can be bound to the ion channel so that the binding of the target molecule controls the ion flow through the channel.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This results in a measurable change in the electrical conduction which is proportional to the concentration of the target.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An ion channel switch (ICS) biosensor can be created using gramicidin, a dimeric peptide channel, in a tethered bilayer membrane.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] One peptide of gramicidin, with attached antibody, is mobile and one is fixed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Breaking the dimer stops the ionic current through the membrane.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The magnitude of the change in electrical signal is greatly increased by separating the membrane from the metal surface using a hydrophilic spacer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Quantitative detection of an extensive class of target species, including proteins, bacteria, drug and toxins has been demonstrated using different membrane and capture configurations.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The European research project Greensense develops a biosensor to perform quantitative screening of drug-of-abuse such as THC, morphine, and cocaine in saliva and urine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A reagentless biosensor can monitor a target analyte in a complex biological mixture without additional reagent.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Therefore, it can function continuously if immobilized on a solid support.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A fluorescent biosensor reacts to the interaction with its target analyte by a change of its fluorescence properties.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A Reagentless Fluorescent biosensor (RF biosensor) can be obtained by integrating a biological receptor, which is directed against the target analyte, and a solvatochromic fluorophore, whose emission properties are sensitive to the nature of its local environment, in a single macromolecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The fluorophore transduces the recognition event into a measurable optical signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The use of extrinsic fluorophores, whose emission properties differ widely from those of the intrinsic fluorophores of proteins, tryptophan and tyrosine, enables one to immediately detect and quantify the analyte in complex biological mixtures.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The integration of the fluorophore must be done in a site where it is sensitive to the binding of the analyte without perturbing the affinity of the receptor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Antibodies and artificial families of Antigen Binding Proteins (AgBP) are well suited to provide the recognition module of RF biosensors since they can be directed against any antigen (see the paragraph on bioreceptors).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A general approach to integrate a solvatochromic fluorophore in an AgBP when the atomic structure of the complex with its antigen is known, and thus transform it into a RF biosensor, has been described.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A residue of the AgBP is identified in the neighborhood of the antigen in their complex.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This residue is changed into a cysteine by site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The fluorophore is chemically coupled to the mutant cysteine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] When the design is successful, the coupled fluorophore does not prevent the binding of the antigen, this binding shields the fluorophore from the solvent, and it can be detected by a change of fluorescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This strategy is also valid for antibody fragments.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] However, in the absence of specific structural data, other strategies must be applied.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Antibodies and artificial families of AgBPs are constituted by a set of hypervariable (or randomized) residue positions, located in a unique sub-region of the protein, and supported by a constant polypeptide scaffold.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The residues that form the binding site for a given antigen, are selected among the hypervariable residues.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This approach is also valid for families of antibody fragments.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The RF biosensors that are obtained by the above methods, can function and detect target analytes inside living cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Magnetic biosensors utilize paramagnetic or supra-paramagnetic particles, or crystals, to detect biological interactions.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Examples could be coil-inductance, resistance, or other magnetic properties.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] It is common to use magnetic nano or microparticles.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In the surface of such particles are the bioreceptors, that can be DNA (complementary to a sequence or aptamers) antibodies, or others.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The binding of the bioreceptor will affect some of the magnetic particle properties that can be measured by AC susceptometry, a Hall Effect sensor, a giant magnetoresistance device, or others.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Piezoelectric sensors utilise crystals which undergo an elastic deformation when an electrical potential is applied to them.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An alternating potential (A.C.) produces a standing wave in the crystal at a characteristic frequency.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This frequency is highly dependent on the elastic properties of the crystal, such that if a crystal is coated with a biological recognition element the binding of a (large) target analyte to a receptor will produce a change in the resonance frequency, which gives a binding signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In a mode that uses surface acoustic waves (SAW), the sensitivity is greatly increased.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Electrochemiluminescence (ECL) is nowadays a leading technique in biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Since the excited species are produced with an electrochemical stimulus rather than with a light excitation source, ECL displays improved signal-to-noise ratio compared to photoluminescence, with minimized effects due to light scattering and luminescence background.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, Later, Leland C.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Clark and Champ Lyons invented the first biosensor in 1962.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensor MOSFETs (BioFETs) were later developed, and they have since been widely used to measure physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The first BioFET was the ion-sensitive field-effect transistor (ISFET), invented by Piet Bergveld for electrochemical and biological applications in 1970. the adsorption FET (ADFET) was patented by P.F.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Cox in 1974, and a hydrogen-sensitive MOSFET was demonstrated by I.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The ISFET is a special type of MOSFET with a gate at a certain distance, and where the metal gate is replaced by an ion-sensitive membrane, electrolyte solution and reference electrode.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The ISFET is widely used in biomedical applications, such as the detection of DNA hybridization, biomarker detection from blood, antibody detection, glucose measurement, pH sensing, and genetic technology.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] By the mid-1980s, other BioFETs had been developed, including the gas sensor FET (GASFET), pressure sensor FET (PRESSFET), chemical field-effect transistor (ChemFET), reference ISFET (REFET), enzyme-modified FET (ENFET) and immunologically modified FET (IMFET).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] By the early 2000s, BioFETs such as the DNA field-effect transistor (DNAFET), gene-modified FET (GenFET) and cell-potential BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The appropriate placement of biosensors depends on their field of application, which may roughly be divided into biotechnology, agriculture, food technology and biomedicine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In biotechnology, analysis of the chemical composition of cultivation broth can be conducted in-line, on-line, at-line and off-line.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] As outlined by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) the sample is not removed from the process stream for in-line sensors, while it is diverted from the manufacturing process for on-line measurements.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] For at-line sensors the sample may be removed and analyzed in close proximity to the process stream.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An example of the latter is the monitoring of lactose in a dairy processing plant.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Off-line biosensors compare to bioanalytical techniques that are not operating in the field, but in the laboratory.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] These techniques are mainly used in agriculture, food technology and biomedicine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In medical applications biosensors are generally categorized as *in vitro* and *in vivo* systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An *in vitro*, biosensor measurement takes place in a test tube, a culture dish, a microtiter plate or elsewhere outside a living organism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The sensor uses a bioreceptor and transducer as outlined above.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An example of an *in vitro* biosensor is an enzyme-conductimetric biosensor for blood glucose monitoring.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There is a challenge to create a biosensor that operates by the principle of point-of-care testing, i.e. at the location where the test is needed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Development of wearable biosensors is among such studies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The elimination of lab testing can save time and money.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An application of a POCT biosensor can be for the testing of HIV in areas where it is difficult for patients to be tested.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A biosensor can be sent directly to the location and a quick and easy test can be used.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An *in vivo* biosensor is an implantable device that operates inside the body.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Of course, biosensor implants have to fulfill the strict regulations on sterilization in order to avoid an initial inflammatory response after implantation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The second concern relates to the long-term biocompatibility, i.e. the unharmful interaction with the body environment during the intended period of use.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] If there is failure, the device must be removed and replaced, causing additional surgery.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An example for application of an in vivo biosensor would be the insulin monitoring within the body, which is not available yet.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Most advanced biosensor implants have been developed for the continuous monitoring of glucose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The figure displays a device, for which a Ti casing and a battery as established for cardiovascular implants like pacemakers and defibrillators is used.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Its size is determined by the battery as required for a lifetime of one year.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Measured glucose data will be transmitted wirelessly out of the body within the MICS 402-405 MHz band as approved for medical implants.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensors can also be integrated into mobile phone systems, making them user-friendly and accessible to a large number of users.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There are many potential applications of biosensors of various types.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A common example of a commercial biosensor is the blood glucose biosensor, which uses the enzyme glucose oxidase to break blood glucose down.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In doing so it first oxidizes glucose and uses two electrons to reduce the FAD (a component of the enzyme) to FADH2.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This in turn is oxidized by the electrode in a number of steps.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The resulting current is a measure of the concentration of glucose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In this case, the electrode is the transducer and the enzyme is the biologically active component.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] A canary in a cage, as used by miners to warn of gas, could be considered a biosensor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Many of today's biosensor applications are similar, in that they use organisms which respond to toxic substances at a much lower concentrations than humans can detect to warn of their presence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Such devices can be used in environmental monitoring, trace gas detection and in water treatment facilities.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Commercially available glucose monitors rely on amperometric sensing of glucose by means of glucose oxidase, which oxidises glucose producing hydrogen peroxide which is detected by the electrode.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] To overcome the limitation of amperometric sensors, a flurry of research is present into novel sensing methods, such as fluorescent glucose biosensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The interferometric reflectance imaging sensor (IRIS) is based on the principles of optical interference and consists of a silicon-silicon oxide substrate, standard optics, and low-powered coherent LEDs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] When light is illuminated through a low magnification objective onto the layered silicon-silicon oxide substrate, an interferometric signature is produced.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] As biomass, which has a similar index of refraction as silicon oxide, accumulates on the substrate surface, a change in the interferometric signature occurs and the change can be correlated to a quantifiable mass.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] *Daaboul et al.* used IRIS to yield a label-free sensitivity of approximately 19 ng/mL.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] *Ahn et al.* improved the sensitivity of IRIS through a mass tagging technique.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Since initial publication, IRIS has been adapted to perform various functions.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] First, IRIS integrated a fluorescence imaging capability into the interferometric imaging instrument as a potential way to address fluorescence protein microarray variability.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Briefly, the variation in fluorescence microarrays mainly derives from inconsistent protein immobilization on surfaces and may cause misdiagnoses in allergy microarrays.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] To correct for any variation in protein immobilization, data acquired in the fluorescence modality is then normalized by the data acquired in the label-free modality.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] IRIS has also been adapted to perform single nanoparticle counting by simply switching the low magnification objective used for label-free biomass quantification to a higher objective magnification.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] This modality enables size discrimination in complex human biological samples.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] *Monroe et al.* used IRIS to quantify protein levels spiked into human whole blood and serum and determined allergen sensitization in characterized human blood samples using zero sample processing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Other practical uses of this device include virus and pathogen detection.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There are several applications of biosensors in food analysis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In the food industry, optics coated with antibodies are commonly used to detect pathogens and food toxins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Commonly, the light system in these biosensors is fluorescence, since this type of optical measurement can greatly amplify the signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] These are in widespread use across the food industry.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensors could be used to monitor air, water, and soil pollutants such as pesticides, potentially carcinogenic, mutagenic, and/or toxic substances and endocrine disrupting chemicals.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] For example, bionanotechnologists developed a viable biosensor, ROSALIND 2.0, that can detect levels of diverse water pollutants.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Because ozone filters out harmful ultraviolet radiation, the discovery of holes in the ozone layer of the earth's atmosphere has raised concern about how much ultraviolet light reaches the earth's surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Of particular concern are the questions of how deeply into sea water ultraviolet radiation penetrates and how it affects marine organisms, especially plankton (floating microorganisms) and viruses that attack plankton.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Plankton form the base of the marine food chains and are believed to affect our planet's temperature and weather by uptake of CO2 for photosynthesis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Deneb Karentz, a researcher at the Laboratory of Radio-biology and Environmental Health (University of California, San Francisco) has devised a simple method for measuring ultraviolet penetration and intensity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Working in the Antarctic Ocean, she submerged to various depths thin plastic bags containing special strains of *E. coli* that are almost totally unable to repair ultraviolet radiation damage to their DNA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Bacterial death rates in these bags were compared with rates in unexposed control bags of the same organism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The bacterial "biosensors" revealed constant significant ultraviolet damage at depths of 10 m and frequently at 20 and 30 m.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Karentz plans additional studies of how ultraviolet may affect seasonal plankton blooms (growth spurts) in the oceans.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer from one part of the body to another via either the circulatory system or lymphatic system.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Unlike radiology imaging tests (mammograms), which send forms of energy (x-rays, magnetic fields, etc.) through the body to only take interior pictures, biosensors have the potential to directly test the malignant power of the tumor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The combination of a biological and detector element allows for a small sample requirement, a compact design, rapid signals, rapid detection, high selectivity and high sensitivity for the analyte being studied.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Compared to the usual radiology imaging tests, biosensors have the advantage of not only finding out how far cancer has spread and checking if treatment is effective but also are cheaper, more efficient (in time, cost and productivity) ways to assess metastaticity in early stages of cancer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biological engineering researchers have created oncological biosensors for breast cancer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Breast cancer is the leading common cancer among women worldwide.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] An example would be a transferrin- quartz crystal microbalance (QCM).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] As a biosensor, quartz crystal microbalances produce oscillations in the frequency of the crystal's standing wave from an alternating potential to detect nano-gram mass changes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] These biosensors are specifically designed to interact and have high selectivity for receptors on cell (cancerous and normal) surfaces.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Ideally, this provides a quantitative detection of cells with this receptor per surface area instead of a qualitative picture detection given by mammograms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Seda Atay, a biotechnology researcher at Hacettepe University, experimentally observed this specificity and selectivity between a QCM and MDA-MB 231 breast cells, MCF 7 cells, and starved MDA-MB 231 cells in vitro.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] With other researchers she devised a method of washing these different metastatic leveled cells over the sensors to measure mass shifts due to different quantities of transferrin receptors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Particularly, the metastatic power of breast cancer cells can be determined by Quartz crystal microbalances with nanoparticles and transferrin that would potentially attach to transferrin receptors on cancer cell surfaces.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] There is very high selectivity for transferrin receptors because they are over-expressed in cancer cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] If cells have high expression of transferrin receptors, which shows their high metastatic power, they have higher affinity and bind more to the QCM that measures the increase in mass.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Depending on the magnitude of the nano-gram mass change, the metastatic power can be determined.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Additionally, in the last years, significant attentions have been focused to detect the biomarkers of lung cancer without biopsy.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] In this regard, biosensors are very attractive and applicable tools for providing rapid, sensitive, specific, stable, cost-effective and non-invasive detections for early lung cancer diagnosis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Thus, cancer biosensors consisting of specific biorecognition molecules such as antibodies, complementary nucleic acid probes or other immobilized biomolecules on a transducer surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] The biorecognition molecules interact specifically with the biomarkers (targets) and the generated biological responses are converted by the transducer into a measurable analytical signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Depending on the type of biological response, various transducers are utilized in the fabrication of cancer biosensors such as electrochemical, optical and mass-based transducers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Biosensors could be used for the detection of pathogenic organisms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Embedded biosensors for pathogenic signatures – such as of SARS-CoV-2 – that are wearable have been developed – such as face masks with built-in tests.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] New types of biosensor-chips could enable novel methods "such as drone-deployed pathogen sensors actively surveying air or wastewater".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Protein-binding aptamers could be used for testing for infectious disease pathogens.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p01] Systems of electronic skins (or robot skins) with built-in biosensors (or chemical sensors) and human-machine interfaces may enable wearable as well as remote sensed device- or robotic-sensing of pathogens (as well as of several hazardous materials and tactile perceptions).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Many optical biosensors are based on the phenomenon of surface plasmon resonance (SPR) techniques.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] This utilises a property of gold and other materials (metals); specifically that a thin layer of gold on a high refractive index glass surface can absorb laser light, producing electron waves (surface plasmons) on the gold surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] This occurs only at a specific angle and wavelength of incident light and is highly dependent on the surface of the gold, such that binding of a target analyte to a receptor on the gold surface produces a measurable signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Surface plasmon resonance sensors operate using a sensor chip consisting of a plastic cassette supporting a glass plate, one side of which is coated with a microscopic layer of gold.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] This side contacts the optical detection apparatus of the instrument.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The opposite side is then contacted with a microfluidic flow system.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The contact with the flow system creates channels across which reagents can be passed in solution.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] This side of the glass sensor chip can be modified in a number of ways, to allow easy attachment of molecules of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Normally it is coated in carboxymethyl dextran or similar compound.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The refractive index at the flow side of the chip surface has a direct influence on the behavior of the light reflected off the gold side.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Binding to the flow side of the chip has an effect on the refractive index and in this way biological interactions can be measured to a high degree of sensitivity with some sort of energy.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The refractive index of the medium near the surface changes when biomolecules attach to the surface, and the SPR angle varies as a function of this change.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Light of a fixed wavelength is reflected off the gold side of the chip at the angle of total internal reflection, and detected inside the instrument.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The angle of incident light is varied in order to match the evanescent wave propagation rate with the propagation rate of the surface plasmon polaritons.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] This induces the evanescent wave to penetrate through the glass plate and some distance into the liquid flowing over the surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Other optical biosensors are mainly based on changes in absorbance or fluorescence of an appropriate indicator compound and do not need a total internal reflection geometry.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] For example, a fully operational prototype device detecting casein in milk has been fabricated.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The device is based on detecting changes in absorption of a gold layer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] A widely used research tool, the micro-array, can also be considered a biosensor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Biological biosensors, also known as optogenetic sensors, often incorporate a genetically modified form of a native protein or enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The protein is configured to detect a specific analyte and the ensuing signal is read by a detection instrument such as a fluorometer or luminometer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] An example of a recently developed biosensor is one for detecting cytosolic concentration of the analyte cAMP (cyclic adenosine monophosphate), a second messenger involved in cellular signaling triggered by ligands interacting with receptors on the cell membrane.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Similar systems have been created to study cellular responses to native ligands or xenobiotics (toxins or small molecule inhibitors).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Such "assays" are commonly used in drug discovery development by pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Most cAMP assays in current use require lysis of the cells prior to measurement of cAMP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] A live-cell biosensor for cAMP can be used in non-lysed cells with the additional advantage of multiple reads to study the kinetics of receptor response.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Nanobiosensors use an immobilized bioreceptor probe that is selective for target analyte molecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Nanomaterials are exquisitely sensitive chemical and biological sensors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Nanoscale materials demonstrate unique properties.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Their large surface area to volume ratio can achieve rapid and low cost reactions, using a variety of designs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Other evanescent wave biosensors have been commercialised using waveguides where the propagation constant through the waveguide is changed by the absorption of molecules to the waveguide surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] One such example, dual polarisation interferometry uses a buried waveguide as a reference against which the change in propagation constant is measured.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Other configurations such as the Mach–Zehnder have reference arms lithographically defined on a substrate.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Higher levels of integration can be achieved using resonator geometries where the resonant frequency of a ring resonator changes when molecules are absorbed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Recently, arrays of many different detector molecules have been applied in so called electronic nose devices, where the pattern of response from the detectors is used to fingerprint a substance.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] In the Wasp Hound odor-detector, the mechanical element is a video camera and the biological element is five parasitic wasps who have been conditioned to swarm in response to the presence of a specific chemical.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Current commercial electronic noses, however, do not use biological elements.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] DNA can be the analyte of a biosensor, being detected through specific means, but it can also be used as part of a biosensor or, theoretically, even as a whole biosensor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Many techniques exist to detect DNA, which is usually a means to detect organisms that have that particular DNA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] DNA sequences can also be used as described above.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] But more forward-looking approaches exist, where DNA can be synthesized to hold enzymes in a biological, stable gel.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Other applications are the design of aptamers, sequences of DNA that have a specific shape to bind a desired molecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The most innovative processes use DNA origami for this, creating sequences that fold in a predictable structure that is useful for detection.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Scientists have built prototype sensors to detect DNA of animals from sucked in air, "airborne eDNA".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] "Nanoantennas" made out of DNA – a novel type of nano-scale optical antenna – can be attached to proteins and produce a signal via fluorescence when these perform their biological functions, in particular for distinct conformational changes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Graphene is a two-dimensional carbon-based substance with superior optical, electrical, mechanical, thermal, and mechanical properties.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] The ability to absorb and immobilize a variety of proteins, particularly some with carbon ring structures, has proven graphene to be an excellent candidate as a biosensor transducer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] As a result, various graphene-based biosensors have been explored and developed in recent times.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Graphene has been employed as a biosensor in various formats especially electrochemical sensors and field effect transistors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] Amongst them graphene field effect transistors (GFETs) especially have shown excellent performance as rapid point of care (PoC) diagnostics as observed through a surge in number of research articles reporting COVID-19 diagnostics using GFETs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] They have been reported to have some of the lowest limit of detection whilst also having a rapid turn around time of a few seconds along with multiplexing abilities.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/biosensor-p02] These capabilities allow for immediate disease detection especially in cases with overlapping symptoms which are hard to distinguish at the outset, thus allowing for better patient outcomes especially in resource strained medical settings.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The **enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay** (**ELISA**) (/ɪˈlaɪzə/, /ˌiːˈlaɪzə/) is a commonly used analytical biochemistry assay, first described by Eva Engvall and Peter Perlmann in 1971.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The assay is a solid-phase type of enzyme immunoassay (EIA) to detect the presence of a ligand (commonly a protein) in a liquid sample using antibodies directed against the ligand to be measured.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA has been used as a diagnostic tool in medicine, plant pathology, and biotechnology, as well as a quality control check in various industries.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In the most simple form of an ELISA, antigens from the sample to be tested are attached to a surface.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Then, a matching antibody is applied over the surface so it can bind the antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This antibody is linked to an enzyme, and then any unbound antibodies are removed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In the final step, a substance containing the enzyme's substrate is added.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] If there was binding, the subsequent reaction produces a detectable signal, most commonly a color change.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Performing an ELISA involves at least one antibody with specificity for a particular antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The sample with an unknown amount of antigen is immobilized on solid support (usually a polystyrene microtiter plate) either non-specifically (via adsorption to the surface) or specifically (via capture by another antibody specific to the same antigen, in a "sandwich" ELISA).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] After the antigen is immobilized, the detection antibody is added, forming a complex with the antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The detection antibody can be covalently linked to an enzyme or can itself be detected by a secondary antibody that is linked to an enzyme through bioconjugation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Between each step, the plate is typically washed with a mild detergent solution to remove any proteins or antibodies that are non-specifically bound.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] After the final wash step, the plate is developed by adding an enzymatic substrate to produce a visible signal, which indicates the quantity of antigen in the sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Of note, ELISA can perform other forms of ligand binding assays instead of strictly "immuno" assays, though the name carried the original "immuno" because of the common use and history of the development of this method.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The technique essentially requires any ligating reagent that can be immobilized on the solid phase along with a detection reagent that will bind specifically and use an enzyme to generate a signal that can be properly quantified.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In between the washes, only the ligand and its specific binding counterparts remain specifically bound or "immunosorbed" by antigen-antibody interactions to the solid phase, while the nonspecific or unbound components are washed away.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Unlike other spectrophotometric wet lab assay formats where the same reaction well (e.g., a cuvette) can be reused after washing, the ELISA plates have the reaction products immunosorbed on the solid phase, which is part of the plate and so are not easily reusable.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This is in contrast to "dry lab" techniques that use dry strips.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Even if the sample is liquid (e.g., a measured small drop), the final detection step in "dry" analysis involves reading of a dried strip by methods such as reflectometry and does not need a reaction containment chamber to prevent spillover or mixing between samples.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] As a heterogenous assay, ELISA separates some components of the analytical reaction mixture by adsorbing certain components onto a solid phase which is physically immobilized.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The quantitative "reading" is usually based on detection of intensity of transmitted light by spectrophotometry, which involves quantitation of transmission of some specific wavelength of light through the liquid (as well as the transparent bottom of the well in the multiple-well plate format).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The sensitivity of detection depends on amplification of the signal during the analytic reactions.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Since enzyme reactions are very well known amplification processes, the signal is generated by enzymes which are linked to the detection reagents in fixed proportions to allow accurate quantification, and thus the name "enzyme-linked".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The analyte is also called the ligand because it will specifically bind or ligate to a detection reagent, thus ELISA falls under the bigger category of ligand binding assays.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Conventionally, like other forms of immunoassays, the specificity of antigen-antibody type reaction is used because it is easy to raise an antibody specifically against an antigen in bulk as a reagent.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Alternatively, if the analyte itself is an antibody, its target antigen can be used as the binding reagent.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Before the development of the ELISA, the only option for conducting an immunoassay was radioimmunoassay, a technique using radioactively labeled antigens or antibodies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In radioimmunoassay, the radioactivity provides the signal, which indicates whether a specific antigen or antibody is present in the sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Radioimmunoassay was first described in a scientific paper by Rosalyn Sussman Yalow and Solomon Berson published in 1960.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] As radioactivity poses a potential health threat, a safer alternative was sought.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A suitable alternative to radioimmunoassay would substitute a nonradioactive signal in place of the radioactive signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] When enzymes (such as horseradish peroxidase) react with appropriate substrates (such as ABTS or TMB), a change in color occurs, which is used as a signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] However, the signal has to be associated with the presence of an antibody or antigen, which is why the enzyme has to be linked to an appropriate antibody.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This linking process was independently developed by Stratis Avrameas and G.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Since it is necessary to remove any unbound antibody or antigen by washing, the antibody or antigen has to be fixed to the surface of the container; i.e., the immunosorbent must be prepared.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A technique to accomplish this was published by Wide and Jerker Porath in 1966.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In 1971, Peter Perlmann and Eva Engvall at Stockholm University in Sweden, and Anton Schuurs and Bauke van Weemen in the Netherlands independently published papers that synthesized this knowledge into methods to perform EIA/ELISA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Traditional ELISA typically involves chromogenic reporters and substrates that produce some observable color change to indicate the presence of antigen or analyte.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Newer ELISA-like techniques use fluorogenic, electrochemiluminescent, and quantitative PCR reporters to create quantifiable signals.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] These new reporters can have various advantages, including higher sensitivities and multiplexing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In technical terms, newer assays of this type are not strictly ELISAs, as they are not "enzyme-linked", but are instead linked to some nonenzymatic reporter.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] However, given that the general principles in these assays are largely similar, they are often grouped in the same category as ELISAs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In 2012, an ultrasensitive, enzyme-based ELISA test using nanoparticles as a chromogenic reporter was able to give a naked-eye colour signal, from the detection of mere attograms of analyte.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A blue color appears for positive results and red color for negative.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Note that this detection only can confirm the presence or the absence of analyte, not the actual concentration.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] There are many ELISA tests for particular molecules that use the matching antibodies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA tests are broken into several types of tests based on how the analytes and antibodies are bonded and used.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The enzyme acts as an amplifier; even if only a few enzyme-linked antibodies remain bound, the enzyme molecules will produce many signal molecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Within common-sense limitations, the enzyme can go on producing color indefinitely, but the more antibody is bound, the faster the color will develop.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The sandwich or indirect ELISA provides a solution to this problem by using a "capture" antibody specific for the test antigen to pull it out of the serum's molecular mixture.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA may be run in a qualitative or quantitative format.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Qualitative results provide a simple positive or negative result (yes or no) for a sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The cutoff between positive and negative is determined by the analyst and may be statistical.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Two or three times the standard deviation (error inherent in a test) is often used to distinguish positive from negative samples.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In quantitative ELISA, the optical density (OD) of the sample is compared to a standard curve, which is typically a serial dilution of a known-concentration solution of the target molecule.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] For example, if a test sample returns an OD of 1.0, the point on the standard curve that gave OD = 1.0 must be of the same analyte concentration as the sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The use and meaning of the names "indirect ELISA" and "direct ELISA" differ in the literature and on websites depending on the context of the experiment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] When the presence of an antigen is analyzed, the name "direct ELISA" refers to an ELISA in which only a labeled primary antibody is used, and the term "indirect ELISA" refers to an ELISA in which the antigen is bound by the primary antibody which then is detected by a labeled secondary antibody.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In the latter case, a sandwich ELISA is clearly distinct from an indirect ELISA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] When the "primary" antibody is of interest, e.g. in the case of immunization analyses, this antibody is directly detected by the secondary antibody and the term "indirect ELISA" applies to a setting with two antibodies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A "sandwich" ELISA is used to detect sample antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Any nonspecific binding sites on the surface are blocked.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The antigen-containing sample is applied to the plate, and captured by antibody.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The plate is washed to remove unbound antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A specific antibody is added, and binds to antigen (hence the 'sandwich': the antigen is stuck between two antibodies).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This primary antibody could be in the serum of a donor, to be tested for reactivity towards the antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Enzyme-linked secondary antibodies are applied as detection antibodies, which bind specifically to the antibody's Fc region (nonspecific).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The plate is washed to remove the unbound antibody-enzyme conjugates.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A chemical is added to be converted by the enzyme into a color, fluorescent, or electrochemical signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The absorbance, fluorescence, or electrochemical signal (e.g., current) of the plate's wells is measured to determine the presence and quantity of the antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The image to the right includes the use of a secondary antibody conjugated to an enzyme, although, in the technical sense, this is not necessary if the primary antibody is conjugated to an enzyme (which would be direct ELISA).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] However, the use of a secondary-antibody conjugate avoids the expensive process of creating enzyme-linked antibodies for every antigen one might want to detect.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] By using an enzyme-linked antibody that binds the Fc region of other antibodies, this same enzyme-linked antibody can be used in a variety of situations.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Without the first layer of "capture" antibody, any proteins in the sample (including serum proteins) may competitively adsorb to the plate surface, lowering the quantity of antigen immobilized.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Use of the purified specific antibody to attach the antigen to the plastic eliminates a need to purify the antigen from complicated mixtures before the measurement, simplifying the assay, and increasing the specificity and the sensitivity of the assay.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Therefore, a sandwich ELISA used for research often needs validation, to reduce the risk of false positive results.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A third use of ELISA is through competitive binding.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Unlabeled antibody is incubated in the presence of its antigen (sample).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The plate is washed, so unbound antibodies are removed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The secondary antibody, specific to the primary antibody, is added.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This second antibody is coupled to the enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A substrate is added, and remaining enzymes elicit a chromogenic or fluorescent signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The reaction is stopped to prevent eventual saturation of the signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Some competitive ELISA kits include enzyme-linked antigen rather than enzyme-linked antibody.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The labeled antigen competes for primary antibody binding sites with the sample antigen (unlabeled).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The less antigen in the sample, the more labeled antigen is retained in the well and the stronger the signal.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Commonly, the antigen is not first positioned in the well.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] For the detection of HIV antibodies, the wells of microtiter plate are coated with the HIV antigen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Two specific antibodies are used, one conjugated with enzyme and the other present in serum (if serum is positive for the antibody).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Cumulative competition occurs between the two antibodies for the same antigen, causing a stronger signal to be seen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Sera to be tested are added to these wells and incubated at 37 °C, and then washed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] If antibodies are present, the antigen-antibody reaction occurs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] No antigen is left for the enzyme-labelled specific HIV antibodies.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] These antibodies remain free upon addition and are washed off during washing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Substrate is added, but there is no enzyme to act on it, so a positive result shows no color change.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A fourth ELISA test does not use the traditional wells, rather leaves the antigens suspended in the test fluid.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A sufficient incubation period is provided to allow the antibodies to bind to the antigens.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The sample is then passed through the Scavenger container.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This can be a test tube or a specifically designed flow through channel.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The surface of the Scavenger container or channel has "Scavenger Antigens" bound to it.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] These can be identical or sufficiently similar to the primary antigens that the free antibodies will bind.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The Scavenger container must have sufficient surface area and sufficient time to allow the Scavenger Antigens to bind to all the excess Antibodies introduced into the sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The sample, that now contains the tagged and bound antibodies, is passed through a detector.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This device can be a flow cytometer or other device that illuminates the tags and registers the response.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This test allows multiple antigens to be tagged and counted at the same time.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This allows specific strains of bacteria to be identified by two (or more) different color tags.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] If both tags are present on a cell, then the cell is that specific strain.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This test is done, generally, one test at a time and cannot be done with the microtiter plate.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The equipment needed is usually less complicated and can be used in the field.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The following table lists the enzymatic markers commonly used in ELISA assays, which allow the results of the assay to be measured upon completion.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Because the ELISA can be performed to evaluate either the presence of antigen or the presence of antibody in a sample, it is a useful tool for determining serum antibody concentrations (such as with the HIV test or West Nile virus).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] It has also found applications in the food industry in detecting potential food allergens, such as milk, peanuts, walnuts, almonds, and eggs and as serological blood test for celiac disease.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA can also be used in toxicology as a rapid presumptive screen for certain classes of drugs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The ELISA was the first screening test widely used for HIV because of its high sensitivity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In an ELISA, a person's serum is diluted 400 times and applied to a plate to which HIV antigens are attached.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] If antibodies to HIV are present in the serum, they may bind to these HIV antigens.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The plate is then washed to remove all other components of the serum.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A specially prepared "secondary antibody"—an antibody that binds to other antibodies—is then applied to the plate, followed by another wash.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This secondary antibody is chemically linked in advance to an enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Thus, the plate will contain enzyme in proportion to the amount of secondary antibody bound to the plate.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A substrate for the enzyme is applied, and catalysis by the enzyme leads to a change in color or fluorescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA results are reported as a number; the most controversial aspect of this test is determining the "cut-off" point between a positive and a negative result.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] A cut-off point may be determined by comparing it with a known standard.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] If an ELISA test is used for drug screening at workplace, a cut-off concentration, 50 ng/ml, for example, is established, and a sample containing the standard concentration of analyte will be prepared.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Unknowns that generate a stronger signal than the known sample are "positive".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Those that generate weaker signal are "negative".
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] There are ELISA tests to detect various kind of diseases, such as dengue, malaria, Chagas disease, Johne's disease, and others.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA tests also are extensively employed for *in vitro* diagnostics in medical laboratories.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] ELISA is as of 2023 the primary method of plant pathogen detection worldwide.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] eSimoa (enzyme-linked single molecule array) represents a significant evolution of the traditional ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) technique, which is widely utilized in clinical diagnostics and research.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] By significantly enhancing the sensitivity and resolution of biomolecular detection, eSimoa expands the capabilities of ELISA, enabling the detection of biomolecules at concentrations previously unachievable with standard assays.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Building on the foundational principles of ELISA, eSimoa employs paramagnetic beads to isolate biomolecules or enzymes in a manner akin to ELISA's plate-based detection.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] However, eSimoa advances this concept by enabling enzymatic reaction measurements at the single-molecule level, which dramatically improves detection limits for various enzymes and biomolecules.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] This method allows for the precise quantification of low-abundance proteins and the activity of critical enzymes such as protein kinases and telomerases, which are often below the detection threshold of conventional ELISA.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The enhanced sensitivity of eSimoa is crucial for early and accurate biomarker detection in clinical diagnostics, facilitating better disease monitoring and management.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] In drug discovery, the ability to track subtle changes in enzymatic activity aids in the development of more effective pharmaceuticals by providing detailed insights into enzyme inhibition mechanisms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] The original work seen on eSimoa was done by David R.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] Walt's team at Harvard University, who published their work in 2020.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/enzyme-linked-immunosorbent-assay] However, the claim to the development of the technology is contested by Chi-An Cheng at National Taiwan University (NTU) in 2023 and 2024, who has claimed that her team developed the technology.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] A **glucose meter,** also referred to as a "**glucometer**", is a medical device for determining the approximate concentration of glucose in the blood.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It can also be a strip of glucose paper dipped into a substance and measured to the glucose chart.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It is a key element of glucose testing, including home blood glucose monitoring (HBGM) performed by people with diabetes mellitus or hypoglycemia.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] A small drop of blood, obtained from slightly piercing a fingertip with a lancet, is placed on a disposable test strip that the meter reads and uses to calculate the blood glucose level.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The meter then displays the level in units of mg/dL or mmol/L.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Since approximately 1980, a primary goal of the management of type 1 diabetes and type 2 diabetes mellitus has been achieving closer-to-normal levels of glucose in the blood for as much of the time as possible, guided by HBGM several times a day.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The benefits include a reduction in the occurrence rate and severity of long-term complications from hyperglycemia as well as a reduction in the short-term, potentially life-threatening complications of hypoglycemia.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Leland Clark presented his first paper about the oxygen electrode, later named the Clark electrode, on 15 April 1956, at a meeting of the American Society for Artificial Organs during the annual meetings of the Federated Societies for Experimental Biology.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In 1962, Clark and Ann Lyons from the Cincinnati Children's Hospital developed the first glucose enzyme electrode.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This biosensor was based on a thin layer of glucose oxidase (GOx) on an oxygen electrode.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Thus, the readout was the amount of oxygen consumed by GOx during the enzymatic reaction with the substrate glucose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This publication became one of the most often cited papers in life sciences.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Due to this work he is considered the “father of biosensors,” especially with respect to the glucose sensing for diabetes patients.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Another early glucose meter was the Ames Reflectance Meter by Anton H.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It was used in American hospitals in the 1970s.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] A moving needle indicated the blood glucose after about a minute.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Home glucose monitoring was demonstrated to improve glycemic control of type 1 diabetes in the late 1970s, and the first meters were marketed for home use around 1981.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The two models initially dominant in North America in the 1980s were the Glucometer, introduced in November 1981, whose trademark is owned by Ascensia Diabetes Care Holdings AG (part of Panasonic Holdings Corporation, now PHC Holdings Corporation), and the Accu-Chek meter (by Roche).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Consequently, these brand names have become synonymous with the generic product to many health care professionals.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In Britain, a health care professional or a patient may refer to "taking a BM": "Mrs X's BM is 5", etc.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] BM stands for Boehringer Mannheim, now part of Roche, who produce test strips called 'BM-test' for use in a meter.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In North America, hospitals resisted adoption of meter glucose measurements for inpatient diabetes care for over a decade.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Managers of laboratories argued that the superior accuracy of a laboratory glucose measurement outweighed the advantage of immediate availability and made meter glucose measurements unacceptable for inpatient diabetes management.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Patients with diabetes and their endocrinologists eventually persuaded acceptance.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Home glucose testing was adopted for type 2 diabetes more slowly than for type 1, and a large proportion of people with type 2 diabetes have never been instructed in home glucose testing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This has mainly come about because health authorities are reluctant to bear the cost of the test strips and lancets.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Test strips that changed color and could be read visually, without a meter, have been widely used since the 1980s.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] They had the added advantage that they could be cut longitudinally to save money.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Critics argued that test strips read by eye are not as accurate or convenient as meter testing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The manufacturer cited studies that show the product is just as effective despite not giving an answer to one decimal place, something they argue is unnecessary for control of blood sugar.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This debate also happened in Germany where "Glucoflex-R" was an established strip for type 2 diabetes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] As meter accuracy and insurance coverage improved, they lost popularity.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] "Glucoflex-R" is Australia manufacturer National Diagnostic Products alternative to the BM test strip.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It has versions that can be used either in a meter or read visually.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It is also marketed under the brand name Betachek.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] On May 1, 2009, the UK distributor Ambe Medical Group reduced the price of their "Glucoflex-R" test strip to the NHS, by approximately 50%.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Special glucose meters for multi-patient hospital use are now used.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] These provide more elaborate quality control records.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Their data handling capabilities are designed to transfer glucose results into electronic medical records and the laboratory computer systems for billing purposes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The cost of home blood glucose monitoring can be substantial due to the cost of the test strips.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In 2006, the US cost to consumers of each glucose strip ranged from about US$0.35 to $1.00.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Manufacturers often provide meters at no cost to encourage use of the profitable test strips.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Type 1 diabetics may test as often as 4 to 10 times a day due to the dynamics of insulin adjustment, whereas type 2 typically test less frequently, especially when insulin is not part of treatment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Batches of counterfeit test strips for some meters were found in the United States, producing erratic test results that do not meet the legitimate manufacturer's performance specifications.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The search for a successful technique began about 1975 and has continued to the present without a clinically or commercially viable product.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] As of 1999, only one such product had ever been approved for sale by the FDA, based on a technique for electrically pulling glucose through intact skin, and it was withdrawn after a short time owing to poor performance and occasional damage to the skin of users.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Continuous glucose monitor systems can consist of a disposable sensor placed under the skin, a transmitter connected to the sensor and a reader that receives and displays the measurements.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The sensor can be used for several days before it needs to be replaced.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The devices provide real-time measurements, and reduce the need for fingerprick testing of glucose levels.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] A drawback is that the meters are not as accurate because they read the glucose levels in the interstitial fluid which lags behind the levels in the blood.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Continuous blood glucose monitoring systems are also relatively expensive.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Accuracy of glucose meters is a common topic of clinical concern.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Blood glucose meters must meet accuracy standards set by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] According to ISO 15197 Blood glucose meters must provide results that are within ±15% of a laboratory standard for concentrations above 100 mg/dL or within ±15 mg/dL for concentrations below 100 mg/dL at least 95% of the time.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] However, a variety of factors can affect the accuracy of a test.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Models vary in their susceptibility to these factors and in their ability to prevent or warn of inaccurate results with error messages.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The Clarke Error Grid has been a common way of analyzing and displaying accuracy of readings related to management consequences.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] More recently an improved version of the Clarke Error Grid has come into use: It is known as the Consensus Error Grid.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Older blood glucose meters often need to be "coded" with the lot of test strips used, otherwise, the accuracy of the blood glucose meter may be compromised due to lack of calibration.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] One noninvasive glucose meter has been approved by the U.S.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] FDA: The GlucoWatch G2 Biographer made by Cygnus Inc.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The device was designed to be worn on the wrist and used electric fields to draw out body fluid for testing.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The device did not replace conventional blood glucose monitoring.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] One limitation was that the GlucoWatch was not able to cope with perspiration at the measurement site.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Sweat must be allowed to dry before measurement can resume.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Due to this limitation and others, the product is no longer on the market.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The market introduction of noninvasive blood glucose measurement by spectroscopic measurement methods, in the field of near-infrared (NIR), by extracorporal measuring devices, has not been successful because the devices measure tissue sugar in body tissues and not the blood sugar in blood fluid.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] To determine blood glucose, the measuring beam of infrared light, for example, has to penetrate the tissue for measurement of blood glucose.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] There are currently three CGMS (continuous glucose monitoring system) available.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The first is Medtronic's Minimed Paradigm RTS with a sub-cutaneous probe attached to a small transmitter (roughly the size of a quarter) that sends interstitial glucose levels to a small pager sized receiver every five minutes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The Dexcom System is another system, available in two different generations in the US, the G4 and the G5.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] It is a hypodermic probe with a small transmitter.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The receiver is about the size of a cell phone and can operate up to twenty feet from the transmitter.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The Dexcom G4 transmits via radio frequency and requires a dedicated receiver.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The G5 version utilizes Bluetooth low energy for data transmission, and can transmit data directly to a compatible cellular telephone.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Currently, Apple's iPhone and Android devices can be used as a receiver.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Aside from a two-hour calibration period, monitoring is logged at five-minute intervals for up to 1 week.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The user can set the high and low glucose alarms.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The third CGMS available is the FreeStyle Navigator from Abbott Laboratories.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] There is currently an effort to develop an integrated treatment system with a glucose meter, insulin pump, and wristop controller, as well as an effort to integrate the glucose meter and a cell phone.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Testing strips are proprietary and available only through the manufacturer (no insurance availability).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] These "Glugophones" are currently offered in three forms: as a dongle for the iPhone, an add-on pack for LG model UX5000, VX5200, and LX350 cell phones, as well as an add-on pack for the Motorola Razr cell phone.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In US, this limits providers to AT&T and Verizon.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Similar systems have been tested for a longer time in Finland.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The first such device, from Telcare, Inc., was exhibited at the 2010 CTIA International Wireless Expo, where it won an E-Tech award.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This device then underwent clinical testing in the US and internationally.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In early 2014 Google reported testing prototypes of contact lenses that monitor glucose levels and alert users when glucose levels cross certain thresholds.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Apple has patented methods for determining blood sugar levels by absorption spectroscopy, as well as by analyzing exhaled air in its electronic devices.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Others use a similar reaction catalysed instead by another enzyme, glucose dehydrogenase (GDH).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This has the advantage of sensitivity over glucose oxidase but is more susceptible to interfering reactions with other substances.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The first-generation devices relied on the same colorimetric reaction that is still used nowadays in glucose test strips for urine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Besides glucose oxidase, the test kit contains a benzidine derivative, which is oxidized to a blue polymer by the hydrogen peroxide formed in the oxidation reaction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The disadvantage of this method was that the test strip had to be developed after a precise interval (the blood had to be washed away), and the meter needed to be calibrated frequently.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Most glucometers today use an electrochemical method.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Test strips contain a capillary that sucks up a reproducible amount of blood.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The glucose in the blood reacts with an enzyme electrode containing glucose oxidase (or dehydrogenase).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The enzyme is reoxidized with an excess of a mediator reagent, such as a ferricyanide ion, a ferrocene derivative or osmium bipyridyl complex.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The mediator in turn is reoxidized by reaction at the electrode, which generates an electric current.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In order for the mediator to operate over long timeframes, it needs to be stable in both oxidised and reduced states.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This is to allow for continuous regeneration of the oxidised form of the mediator for shuttling of electrons from enzyme to active site.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Osmium-based polypyridyl redox complexes and polymers are attractive candidates as mediators due to their stability in oxidised and reduced forms, tunable redox potential, ease of co-immobilisation and ability to operate at low potentials.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The total charge passing through the electrode is proportional to the amount of glucose in the blood that has reacted with the enzyme.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The coulometric method is a technique where the total amount of charge generated by the glucose oxidation reaction is measured over a period of time.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The amperometric method is used by some meters and measures the electric current generated at a specific point in time by the glucose reaction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] This is analogous to throwing a ball and using the speed at which it is travelling at a point in time to estimate how hard it was thrown.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The coulometric method can allow for variable test times, whereas the test time on a meter using the amperometric method is always fixed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Both methods give an estimation of the concentration of glucose in the initial blood sample.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The same principle is used in test strips that have been commercialized for the detection of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] These test strips use a beta-hydroxybutyrate-dehydrogenase enzyme instead of a glucose oxidizing enzyme and have been used to detect and help treat some of the complications that can result from prolonged hyperglycemia.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Blood alcohol sensors using the same approach, but with alcohol dehydrogenase enzymes, have been tried and patented but have not yet been successfully commercially developed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] Although the apparent value of immediate measurement of blood glucose might seem to be higher for hypoglycemia (low sugar) than hyperglycemia (high sugar), meters have been less useful.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The primary problems are *precision* and *ratio of false positive and negative results*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] An imprecision of ±15% is less of a problem for high glucose levels than low.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] There is little difference in the management of a glucose of 200 mg/dL compared with 260 (i.e., a "true" glucose of 230±15%), but a ±15% error margin at a low glucose concentration brings greater ambiguity with regards to glucose management.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] The imprecision is compounded by the relative likelihoods of false positives and negatives in populations with diabetes and those without.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] In contrast, people who do not have diabetes may periodically have hypoglycemic symptoms but may also have a much higher rate of false positives to true, and a meter is not accurate enough to base a diagnosis of hypoglycemia upon.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/glucose-meter] A meter can occasionally be useful in the monitoring of severe types of hypoglycemia (e.g., congenital hyperinsulinism) to ensure that the average glucose when fasting remains above 70 mg/dL (3.9 mmol/L).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The **green fluorescent protein** (**GFP**) is a protein that exhibits green fluorescence when exposed to light in the blue to ultraviolet range.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The label *GFP* traditionally refers to the protein first isolated from the jellyfish *Aequorea victoria* and is sometimes called *avGFP*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, GFPs have been found in other organisms including corals, sea anemones, zoanithids, copepods and lancelets.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The GFP from *A. victoria* has a major excitation peak at a wavelength of 395 nm and a minor one at 475 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Its emission peak is at 509 nm, which is in the lower green portion of the visible spectrum.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The fluorescence quantum yield (QY) of GFP is 0.79.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The GFP from the sea pansy (*Renilla reniformis*) has a single major excitation peak at 498 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP makes for an excellent tool in many forms of biology due to its ability to form an internal chromophore without requiring any accessory cofactors, gene products, or enzymes / substrates other than molecular oxygen.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In cell and molecular biology, the GFP gene is frequently used as a reporter of expression.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] It has been used in modified forms to make biosensors, and many animals have been created that express GFP, which demonstrates a proof of concept that a gene can be expressed throughout a given organism, in selected organs, or in cells of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP can be introduced into animals or other species through transgenic techniques, and maintained in their genome and that of their offspring.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP has been expressed in many species, including bacteria, yeasts, fungi, fish and mammals, including in human cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Tsien, Osamu Shimomura, and Martin Chalfie were awarded the 2008 Nobel Prize in Chemistry on 10 October 2008 for their discovery and development of the green fluorescent protein.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Most commercially available genes for GFP and similar fluorescent proteins are around 730 base-pairs long.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The natural protein has 238 amino acids.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Therefore, fusing the GFP gene to the gene of a protein of interest can significantly increase the protein's size and molecular mass, and can impair the protein's natural function or change its location or trajectory of transport within the cell.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In the 1960s and 1970s, GFP, along with the separate luminescent protein aequorin (an enzyme that catalyzes the breakdown of luciferin, releasing light), was first purified from the jellyfish *Aequorea victoria* and its properties studied by Osamu Shimomura.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In *A. victoria*, GFP fluorescence occurs when aequorin interacts with Ca2+ ions, inducing a blue glow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Some of this luminescent energy is transferred to the GFP, shifting the overall color towards green.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, its utility as a tool for molecular biologists did not begin to be realized until 1992 when Douglas Prasher reported the cloning and nucleotide sequence of wtGFP in *Gene*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The funding for this project had run out, so Prasher sent cDNA samples to several labs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The lab of Martin Chalfie expressed the coding sequence of wtGFP, with the first few amino acids deleted, in heterologous cells of *E. coli* and *C. elegans*, publishing the results in *Science* in 1994.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Frederick Tsuji's lab independently reported the expression of the recombinant protein one month later.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Remarkably, the GFP molecule folded and was fluorescent at room temperature, without the need for exogenous cofactors specific to the jellyfish.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Although this near-wtGFP was fluorescent, it had several drawbacks, including dual peaked excitation spectra, pH sensitivity, chloride sensitivity, poor fluorescence quantum yield, poor photostability and poor folding at 37 °C (99 °F).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The first reported crystal structure of a GFP was that of the S65T mutant by the Remington group in *Science* in 1996.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] One month later, the Phillips group independently reported the wild-type GFP structure in *Nature Biotechnology*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These crystal structures provided vital background on chromophore formation and neighboring residue interactions.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Researchers have modified these residues by directed and random mutagenesis to produce the wide variety of GFP derivatives in use since then.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Further research into GFP has shown that it is resistant to detergents, proteases, guanidinium chloride (GdmCl) treatments, and drastic temperature changes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Due to the potential for widespread usage and the evolving needs of researchers, many different mutants of GFP have been engineered.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The first major improvement was a single point mutation (S65T) reported in 1995 in *Nature* by Roger Tsien.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This mutation dramatically improved the spectral characteristics of GFP, resulting in increased fluorescence, photostability, and a shift of the major excitation peak to 488 nm, with the peak emission kept at 509 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This matched the spectral characteristics of commonly available FITC filter sets, increasing the practicality of use by the general researcher.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] A 37 °C folding efficiency (F64L) point mutant to this scaffold, yielding enhanced GFP (EGFP), was discovered in 1995 by the laboratories of Thastrup and Falkow.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] EGFP allowed the practical use of GFPs in mammalian cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] EGFP has an extinction coefficient (denoted ε) of 55,000 M−1cm−1.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The fluorescence quantum yield (QY) of EGFP is 0.60.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The relative brightness, expressed as ε•QY, is 33,000 M−1cm−1.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The widely used EGFP sequence, however, may produce an unintended protein product, using the +2 frame as the template.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Superfolder GFP (sfGFP), a series of mutations that allow GFP to rapidly fold and mature even when fused to poorly folding peptides, was reported in 2006.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Many other mutations have been made, including color mutants; in particular, blue fluorescent protein (EBFP, EBFP2, Azurite, mKalama1), cyan fluorescent protein (ECFP, Cerulean, CyPet, mTurquoise2), and yellow fluorescent protein derivatives (YFP, Citrine, Venus, YPet).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] BFP derivatives (except mKalama1) contain the Y66H substitution.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] They exhibit a broad absorption band in the ultraviolet centered close to 380 nanometers and an emission maximum at 448 nanometers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] A green fluorescent protein mutant (BFPms1) that preferentially binds Zn(II) and Cu(II) has been developed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] BFPms1 have several important mutations including and the BFP chromophore (Y66H),Y145F for higher quantum yield, H148G for creating a hole into the beta-barrel and several other mutations that increase solubility.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Zn(II) binding increases fluorescence intensity, while Cu(II) binding quenches fluorescence and shifts the absorbance maximum from 379 to 444 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Therefore, they can be used as a Zn biosensor.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] More color variants are possible via chromophore binding.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The critical mutation in cyan derivatives is the Y66W substitution, which causes the chromophore to form with an indole rather than phenol component.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Several additional compensatory mutations in the surrounding barrel are required to restore brightness to this modified chromophore due to the increased bulk of the indole group.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In ECFP and Cerulean, the N-terminal half of the seventh strand exhibits two conformations.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These conformations both have a complex set of van der Waals interactions with the chromophore.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The Y145A and H148D mutations in Cerulean stabilize these interactions and allow the chromophore to be more planar, better packed, and less prone to collisional quenching.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Additional site-directed random mutagenesis in combination with fluorescence lifetime based screening has further stabilized the seventh β-strand resulting in a bright variant, mTurquoise2, with a quantum yield (QY) of 0.93.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The red-shifted wavelength of the YFP derivatives is accomplished by the T203Y mutation and is due to π-electron stacking interactions between the substituted tyrosine residue and the chromophore.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These two classes of spectral variants are often employed for Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) experiments.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Genetically encoded FRET reporters sensitive to cell signaling molecules, such as calcium or glutamate, protein phosphorylation state, protein complementation, receptor dimerization, and other processes provide highly specific optical readouts of cell activity in real time.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Semirational mutagenesis of a number of residues led to pH-sensitive mutants known as pHluorins, and later super-ecliptic pHluorins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] By exploiting the rapid change in pH upon synaptic vesicle fusion, pHluorins tagged to synaptobrevin have been used to visualize synaptic activity in neurons.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Redox sensitive GFP (roGFP) was engineered by introduction of cysteines into the beta barrel structure.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The redox state of the cysteines determines the fluorescent properties of roGFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The nomenclature of modified GFPs is often confusing due to overlapping mapping of several GFP versions onto a single name.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] For example, **mGFP** often refers to a GFP with an N-terminal palmitoylation that causes the GFP to bind to cell membranes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, the same term is also used to refer to monomeric GFP, which is often achieved by the dimer interface breaking A206K mutation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Wild-type GFP has a weak dimerization tendency at concentrations above 5 mg/mL. mGFP also stands for "modified GFP", which has been optimized through amino acid exchange for stable expression in plant cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The purpose of both the (primary) bioluminescence (from aequorin's action on luciferin) and the (secondary) fluorescence of GFP in jellyfish is unknown.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP is co-expressed with aequorin in small granules around the rim of the jellyfish bell.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The secondary excitation peak (480 nm) of GFP does absorb some of the blue emission of aequorin, giving the bioluminescence a more green hue.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The serine 65 residue of the GFP chromophore is responsible for the dual-peaked excitation spectra of wild-type GFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] It is conserved in all three GFP isoforms originally cloned by Prasher.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Nearly all mutations of this residue consolidate the excitation spectra to a single peak at either 395 nm or 480 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The precise mechanism of this sensitivity is complex, but, it seems, involves donation of a hydrogen from serine 65 to glutamate 222, which influences chromophore ionization.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Since a single mutation can dramatically enhance the 480 nm excitation peak, making GFP a much more efficient partner of aequorin, *A. victoria* appears to evolutionarily prefer the less-efficient, dual-peaked excitation spectrum.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Roger Tsien has speculated that varying hydrostatic pressure with depth may affect serine 65's ability to donate a hydrogen to the chromophore and shift the ratio of the two excitation peaks.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Thus, the jellyfish may change the color of its bioluminescence with depth.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, a collapse in the population of jellyfish in Friday Harbor, where GFP was originally discovered, has hampered further study of the role of GFP in the jellyfish's natural environment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Most species of lancelet are known to produce GFP in various regions of their body.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Unlike *A. victoria*, lancelets do not produce their own blue light, and the origin of their endogenous GFP is still unknown.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Some speculate that it attracts plankton towards the mouth of the lancelet, serving as a passive hunting mechanism.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] It may also serve as a photoprotective agent in the larvae, preventing damage caused by high-intensity blue light by converting it into lower-intensity green light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, these theories have not been tested.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP-like proteins have been found in multiple species of marine copepods, particularly from the Pontellidae and Aetideidae families.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] There are many GFP-like proteins that, despite being in the same protein family as GFP, are not directly derived from *Aequorea victoria*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These include dsRed, eqFP611, Dronpa, TagRFPs, KFP, EosFP/IrisFP, Dendra, and so on.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Having been developed from proteins in different organisms, these proteins can sometimes display unanticipated approaches to chromophore formation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Some of these, such as KFP, are developed from naturally non- or weakly-fluorescent proteins to be greatly improved upon by mutagenesis.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] When GFP-like barrels of different spectral characteristics are used, the excitation spectrum of one chromophore can be used to power another chromophore (FRET), allowing for conversion between wavelengths of light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] FMN-binding fluorescent proteins (FbFPs) were developed in 2007 and are a class of small (11–16 kDa), oxygen-independent fluorescent proteins that are derived from blue-light receptors.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] They are intended especially for the use under anaerobic or hypoxic conditions, since the formation and binding of the flavin chromophore does not require molecular oxygen, as it is the case with the synthesis of the GFP chromophore.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Fluorescent proteins with other chromophores, such as UnaG with bilirubin, can display unique properties like red-shifted emission above 600 nm or photoconversion from a green-emitting state to a red-emitting state.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] They can have excitation and emission wavelengths far enough apart to achieve conversion between red and green light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Reviews on new classes of fluorescent proteins and applications can be found in the cited reviews.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP has a beta barrel structure consisting of eleven β-strands with a pleated sheet arrangement, with an alpha helix containing the covalently bonded chromophore 4-(*p*-hydroxybenzylidene)imidazolidin-5-one (HBI) running through the center.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Five shorter alpha helices form caps on the ends of the structure.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The beta barrel structure is a nearly perfect cylinder, 42Å long and 24Å in diameter (some studies have reported a diameter of 30Å), creating what is referred to as a "β-can" formation, which is unique to the GFP-like family.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] HBI, the spontaneously modified form of the tripeptide Ser65–Tyr66–Gly67, is nonfluorescent in the absence of the properly folded GFP scaffold and exists mainly in the un-ionized phenol form in wtGFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Inward-facing sidechains of the barrel induce specific cyclization reactions in Ser65–Tyr66–Gly67 that induce ionization of HBI to the phenolate form and chromophore formation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This process of post-translational modification is referred to as *maturation*.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The hydrogen-bonding network and electron-stacking interactions with these sidechains influence the color, intensity and photostability of GFP and its numerous derivatives.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The tightly packed nature of the barrel excludes solvent molecules, protecting the chromophore fluorescence from quenching by water.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In addition to the auto-cyclization of the Ser65-Tyr66-Gly67, a 1,2-dehydrogenation reaction occurs at the Tyr66 residue.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Besides the three residues that form the chromophore, residues such as Gln94, Arg96, His148, Thr203, and Glu222 all act as stabilizers.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The residues of Gln94, Arg96, and His148 are able to stabilize by delocalizing the chromophore charge.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Arg96 is the most important stabilizing residue due to the fact that it prompts the necessary structural realignments that are necessary from the HBI ring to occur.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Any mutation to the Arg96 residue would result in a decrease in the development rate of the chromophore because proper electrostatic and steric interactions would be lost.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Tyr66 is the recipient of hydrogen bonds and does not ionize in order to produce favorable electrostatics.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Blue fluorescent protein (BFP) is the blue variant of green fluorescent protein (GFP).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] BFP has a very similar structure to GFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In the BFP structure, two substitution mutations in the amino acid sequence change its fluorescence from green to blue.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The first mutation occurs inside the chromophore of GFP at position 66 which changes a tyrosine to a histidine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The other mutation in BFP is on the tyrosine at position 145 which mutates to phenylalanine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The autocatalytic cyclization and oxidation of the serine, tyrosine, and glycine form the GFP chromophore.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These three residues at positions 65-67 make up the green fluorescent chromophore.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] When the tyrosine in the chromophore is substituted by a histidine, it changes the folding structure of the protein and emission spectra.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The T145F mutation is also added to increase the stability of the protein and well as intensify the fluorescence.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] These mutations are what change GFP to BFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Mechanistically, the process involves base-mediated cyclization followed by dehydration and oxidation.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In the reaction of 7a to 8 involves the formation of an enamine from the imine, while in the reaction of 7b to 9 a proton is abstracted.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The formed HBI fluorophore is highlighted in green.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The reactions are catalyzed by residues Glu222 and Arg96.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] An analogous mechanism is also possible with threonine in place of Ser65.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Green fluorescent protein may be used as a reporter gene.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] For example, GFP can be used as a reporter for environmental toxicity levels.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This protein has been shown to be an effective way to measure the toxicity levels of various chemicals including ethanol, *p*-formaldehyde, phenol, triclosan, and paraben.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP is great as a reporter protein because it has no effect on the host when introduced to the host's cellular environment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Due to this ability, no external visualization stain, ATP, or cofactors are needed.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] With regards to pollutant levels, the fluorescence was measured in order to gauge the effect that the pollutants have on the host cell.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The cellular density of the host cell was also measured.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Results from the study conducted by Song, Kim, & Seo (2016) showed that there was a decrease in both fluorescence and cellular density as pollutant levels increased.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This was indicative of the fact that cellular activity had decreased.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] More research into this specific application in order to determine the mechanism by which GFP acts as a pollutant marker.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Similar results have been observed in zebrafish because zebrafish that were injected with GFP were approximately twenty times more susceptible to recognize cellular stresses than zebrafish that were not injected with GFP.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The biggest advantage of GFP is that it can be heritable, depending on how it was introduced, allowing for continued study of cells and tissues it is expressed in.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Visualizing GFP is noninvasive, requiring only illumination with blue light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP alone does not interfere with biological processes, but when fused to proteins of interest, careful design of linkers is required to maintain the function of the protein of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Moreover, if used with a monomer it is able to diffuse readily throughout cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The availability of GFP and its derivatives has thoroughly redefined fluorescence microscopy and the way it is used in cell biology and other biological disciplines.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] While most small fluorescent molecules such as FITC (fluorescein isothiocyanate) are strongly phototoxic when used in live cells, fluorescent proteins such as GFP are usually much less harmful when illuminated in living cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This has triggered the development of highly automated live-cell fluorescence microscopy systems, which can be used to observe cells over time expressing one or more proteins tagged with fluorescent proteins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] There are many techniques to utilize GFP in a live cell imaging experiment.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The most direct way of utilizing GFP is to directly attach it to a protein of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] For example, GFP can be included in a plasmid expressing other genes to indicate a successful transfection of a gene of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Another method is to use a GFP that contains a mutation where the fluorescence will change from green to yellow over time, which is referred to as a fluorescent timer.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] With the fluorescent timer, researchers can study the state of protein production such as recently activated, continuously activated, or recently deactivated based on the color reported by the fluorescent protein.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In yet another example, scientists have modified GFP to become active only after exposure to irradiation giving researchers a tool to selectively activate certain portions of a cell and observe where proteins tagged with the GFP move from the starting location.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] For example, GFP had been widely used in labelling the spermatozoa of various organisms for identification purposes as in *Drosophila melanogaster*, where expression of GFP can be used as a marker for a particular characteristic.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP can also be expressed in different structures enabling morphological distinction.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In cells where the gene is expressed, and the tagged proteins are produced, GFP is produced at the same time.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Thus, only those cells in which the tagged gene is expressed, or the target proteins are produced, will fluoresce when observed under fluorescence microscopy.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Analysis of such time lapse movies has redefined the understanding of many biological processes including protein folding, protein transport, and RNA dynamics, which in the past had been studied using fixed (i.e., dead) material.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Obtained data are also used to calibrate mathematical models of intracellular systems and to estimate rates of gene expression.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Similarly, GFP can be used as an indicator of protein expression in heterologous systems.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In this scenario, fusion proteins containing GFP are introduced indirectly, using RNA of the construct, or directly, with the tagged protein itself.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This method is useful for studying structural and functional characteristics of the tagged protein on a macromolecular or single-molecule scale with fluorescence microscopy.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The Vertico SMI microscope using the SPDM Phymod technology uses the so-called "reversible photobleaching" effect of fluorescent dyes like GFP and its derivatives to localize them as single molecules in an optical resolution of 10 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This can also be performed as a co-localization of two GFP derivatives (2CLM).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Another powerful use of GFP is to express the protein in small sets of specific cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This allows researchers to optically detect specific types of cells *in vitro* (in a dish), or even *in vivo* (in the living organism).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP is considered to be a reliable reporter of gene expression in eukaryotic cells when the fluorescence is measured by flow cytometry.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Genetically combining several spectral variants of GFP is a useful trick for the analysis of brain circuitry (Brainbow).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Other interesting uses of fluorescent proteins in the literature include using FPs as sensors of neuron membrane potential, tracking of AMPA receptors on cell membranes, viral entry and the infection of individual influenza viruses and lentiviral viruses, etc.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] It has also been found that new lines of transgenic GFP rats can be relevant for gene therapy as well as regenerative medicine.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] By using "high-expresser" GFP, transgenic rats display high expression in most tissues, and many cells that have not been characterized or have been only poorly characterized in previous GFP-transgenic rats.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP has been shown to be useful in cryobiology as a viability assay.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Correlation of viability as measured by trypan blue assays were 0.97.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Another application is the use of GFP co-transfection as internal control for transfection efficiency in mammalian cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] A novel possible use of GFP includes using it as a sensitive monitor of intracellular processes via an eGFP laser system made out of a human embryonic kidney cell line.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The first engineered living laser is made by an eGFP expressing cell inside a reflective optical cavity and hitting it with pulses of blue light.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] At a certain pulse threshold, the eGFP's optical output becomes brighter and completely uniform in color of pure green with a wavelength of 516 nm.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Before being emitted as laser light, the light bounces back and forth within the resonator cavity and passes the cell numerous times.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] By studying the changes in optical activity, researchers may better understand cellular processes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP is used widely in cancer research to label and track cancer cells.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP-labelled cancer cells have been used to model metastasis, the process by which cancer cells spread to distant organs.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] GFP can be used to analyse the colocalization of proteins.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] This is achieved by "splitting" the protein into two fragments which are able to self-assemble, and then fusing each of these to the two proteins of interest.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Alone, these incomplete GFP fragments are unable to fluoresce.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] However, if the two proteins of interest colocalize, then the two GFP fragments assemble together to form a GFP-like structure which is able to fluoresce.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Therefore, by measuring the level of fluorescence it is possible to determine whether the two proteins of interest colocalize.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Macro-scale biological processes, such as the spread of virus infections, can be followed using GFP labeling.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In the past, mutagenic ultra violet light (UV) has been used to illuminate living organisms (e.g., see) to detect and photograph the GFP expression.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Recently, a technique using non-mutagenic LED lights have been developed for macro-photography.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The technique uses an epifluorescence camera attachment based on the same principle used in the construction of epifluorescence microscopes.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Alba, a green-fluorescent rabbit, was created by a French laboratory commissioned by Eduardo Kac using GFP for purposes of art and social commentary.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The US company Yorktown Technologies markets to aquarium shops green fluorescent zebrafish (GloFish) that were initially developed to detect pollution in waterways.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] NeonPets, a US-based company has marketed green fluorescent mice to the pet industry as NeonMice.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Green fluorescent pigs, known as Noels, were bred by a group of researchers led by Wu Shinn-Chih at the Department of Animal Science and Technology at National Taiwan University.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] A Japanese-American Team created green-fluorescent cats as proof of concept to use them potentially as model organisms for diseases, particularly HIV.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] In 2009 a South Korean team from Seoul National University bred the first transgenic beagles with fibroblast cells from sea anemones.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The dogs give off a red fluorescent light, and they are meant to allow scientists to study the genes that cause human diseases like narcolepsy and blindness.
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] Julian Voss-Andreae, a German-born artist specializing in "protein sculptures", created sculptures based on the structure of GFP, including the 1.70 metres (5 feet 7 inches) tall "Green Fluorescent Protein" (2004) and the 1.40 metres (4 feet 7 inches) tall "Steel Jellyfish" (2006).
[src:biosensors-synthetic/green-fluorescent-protein] The latter sculpture is located at the place of GFP's discovery by Shimomura in 1962, the University of Washington's Friday Harbor Laboratories.
